commit_message:
raise exception when no neutron support in create server of v3 api

this fix bug:1208743. But this test in this bug is failed becuase
when there is no neutron support in create server of v3 api, it will
set requset_networks none, and no corresponding response to user. the uuid
check is in _get_requested_networks will be skipped because the
requset_networks is none.

Change-Id: I966507c2cd42b8527c3cbd6ae05f30e33e7d059b

"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-08-07 14:58:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

With ack_on_error=False, the message won't be stored anyway if there's an error, so it won't come back, so your check won't prevent it to try again to be stored?
I miss the case I think."}, {'account_id': 688, 'date': '2013-08-07 15:17:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@jd ... depends on where in the pipeline the error occurs. We've run into this problem with StackTach. The most important thing is to persist the event, but the pipeline could fail downstream. It throws an exception and requeues the event. So, when we get the event again, we resave it and it fails again. We've blown out mysql on this loop. This use-case can be avoided on how you construct your pipeline or when you persist the event. But it's a sanity check just in case."}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-08-08 09:25:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

If you fail to save, anyway you won't be able to check in the database since it won't be in there, or do I miss something?

And even if it is, the fact that you reject the message is likely to cause it to stay in AMQP queue for ever, no?"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-16 06:03:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-16 06:03:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}]

When ack_on_error=False, there is a possibility that we

Change-Id: I8eeecd5ffe1416b03aae7c7e6003407c45530702
'}]
commit_message:
Reject duplicate events

When ack_on_error=False, there is a possibility that we
could receieve the same message more than once. Reject those events.

Change-Id: I8eeecd5ffe1416b03aae7c7e6003407c45530702

commit_message:
Unbreak the pip/setuptools install on fedora

There are issues with how fedora installs python packages via pip (by
installing them inexplicably into /usr in violation of every aspect of
everything about the FHS) Add a ridiculous and uncalled for workaround
that downloads the tarballs, then uninstalls setuptools, then installs
setuptools and pip from source.

Change-Id: Idb8ff2e790b1480ca1b0d4bb414d7502b516a378

subject: Add os-periodic-task-on-demand API
messages:
[{'account_id': 6661, 'date': '2013-08-07 20:35:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Work In Progress

This isn't fully baked yet."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-08-07 20:38:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Some initial comments on the current state ...

1) I'm not sure we would want to expose this publicly.  This could be a candidate for a new admin API that I'm looking at adding for another reason.

2) I don't think method names should be exposed via the API.  In general, I don't think internal implementation details should be exposed.

3) I don't think the API should refer to "periodic" tasks at all.  The fact that these operations may run periodically is separate.  It's more of an admin cleanup task that also may be run internally periodically.

4) If we wanted to go crazy, we could have this able to run tasks as a one-shot, or to enable/disable running them periodically.  I'm not sure if there's really a good use case for that, though.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-07 21:31:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Doesn't seem to work

[{'created': '2013-07-19 09:18:46.000000000', 'message': 'Added plugin (e.g. network) to monitor and collect resource data

    This patch gives a plugin interface for users to add their own plugins to
    monitor resources on compute nodes on the compute manager.

    The compute manager loads the plugins and gets the metrics, and sends to
    the scheduler for utilization based scheduling.
    The patch also gives a sample to collect network utilization data.

    This is part of the blueprint utilization-aware-scheduling and the
    blueprint generic-host-state-for-scheduler.

Change-Id: I301f05614bc2ac7bed3b5c7be82b040844185797

commit_message:
Added plugin (e.g. network) to monitor and collect resource data

    This patch gives a plugin interface for users to add their own plugins to
    monitor resources on compute nodes on the compute manager.

    The compute manager loads the plugins and gets the metrics, and sends to
    the scheduler for utilization based scheduling.
    The patch also gives a sample to collect network information.

Change-Id: I301f05614bc2ac7bed3b5c7be82b040844185797

commit_message:
grub2.0 is not available on RHEL derivatives

grub0.97 is available on RHEL6, CentOS, Scientific Linux, and SUSE.
Instead move the grub configuration to fedora and ubuntu finalise.d
steps.

commit_message:
Move nova LVM utilities to oslo

This is the first step in reusing these methods in cinder. These
methods in nova had no unit tests, so I have added test coverage
as part of moving them to oslo.

Review I4dd8d1e343d1c182255a2b2188a9c8572a01394b moves nova
across to this new oslo module.

Progresses blueprint de-duplicate-lvm-utils.

Change-Id: Ib55861987b2bb4bbc6ed6e350ad34a85bfc3c30a

My read of the thread was different - most people don't care, don't want to waste time discussing it but there is a reasonable level of consensus that ending in a period isn't good practice

The case for this check is that we've seen a project enforcing the opposite policy. Which suggests some people do care about stuff like this and will make people re-spin their patch for it. Having the check in hacking means people know upfront what the recommended style is and how to avoid falling foul of nitpickers.

Anyway ... so long as I never again see people -1ing patches for this stuff, I really don't care either way. But I wonder ... given our love of nitpicking, how realistic is that?"}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-06-26 19:36:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Since most people don't care much either way, but some projects have taken different approaches.  I think this would be best kept as a local check in projects (or the inverse check).  That way we don't have to -1 over periods.  and different projects can take different approaches."}, {'account_id': 6593, 'date': '2013-06-26 23:23:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Wouldn't it be easier to have projects that *don't* want it blacklist this in their tox.ini rather than having each project to copy this check (and adding different level of bugs to it possibly)?"}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-06-27 00:34:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The feeling I've gotten from the list thread are that a) we have quite a few people using sentences in their commit messages; b) most folk don't care if they see a period or not, and c) there is no strong will to force it one way or the other.

In TripleO we are no longer requiring a period, but neither would we want to break folk that do use good grammar but prohibiting them. This check just seems unneeded and not broadly supported."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-06-27 00:34:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 6593, 'date': '2013-06-27 06:35:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2013-06-27 14:38:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm with Mark on this one, I'd rather just leave the check, and not have -1 fights over periods in reviews. Not being strict leads to more review work."}, {'account_id': 6593, 'date': '2013-07-03 12:01:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I think it is easy enough to ignore (blacklist) this particular check for those who do not want to care. For those who care or are undecided, having the warning by default is imho good."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-07-03 13:00:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

From what I can tell this is not a care vs don't care issue.  This is a agree, disagree or don't care issue.  

And the question is should we enforce caring by default, not caring or even the opposite?

If we don't have consensus on the enforce period or enforce no period decision and most people don't care then I recommend reverting this and enforce the 'don't care' policy."}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2013-07-05 14:48:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm with Sean and Mark. We have several arbitrary style rules that aren't necessarily 100% consensus - but having the rule and enforcing it, I believe, will be better in the long run. If a project REALLY has a beef with it, they can always disable the check. (although we should, at some point, make a gate job that checks the openstack projects do not add new hacking exclusions...)"}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-07-09 08:30:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

looks like majority of people want to leave this one around'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-07-31 23:01:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ugh, I missed this being abandoned. How do I disable this check in the tripleo projects?'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-08-01 00:52:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Add H803 to the tox.ini file and add a note in there saying its ignored on purpose'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-08-01 00:53:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Add it to the list of ignores in flake8'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-08-01 03:36:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So, all the tripleo projects will be blacklisting H* checks, as they clearly don't represent the community consensus. This seems suboptimal to me : where there is consensus [in this case it was 'just ignore periods, present or absent - whatever], we should honour that."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-08-02 00:08:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Restored'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-08-02 00:08:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-02 00:50:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- http://logs.openstack.org/01/34601/2/check/gate-hacking-pep8/9968d9e : SUCCESS in 43s
- http://docs-draft.openstack.org/01/34601/2/check/gate-hacking-docs/65e4e96/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 44s

'}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2013-08-02 19:18:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-08-02 19:38:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Do not merge

Don't see what's changed since the previous discussion on this"}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-08-02 21:39:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The consensus was that a) enforcing it in any direction is a bad idea and waste of time- lets just code and I'm very willing to follow that consensus. I updated the wiki page to say explicitly that it wasn't criteria for rejecting a patch (though that has been reverted, so I'll need to reinstate it when this lands).

This rule was added to hacking without broad discussion, once broad discussion was had it is clearly inappropriate, and the earlier discussion on this proposal boiled down to two things:

a- what if someone other than Robert also goes crazy and enforces grammar in commit lines?

b- hey it's arbitrary but we have lots of arbitrary so thats cool.

for a: thats why the docs on the wiki were updated by me; if anyone debates they *can* be pointed at the explicit statement the community has reached.

for b: well arbitrary is tolerable when there are benefits to consistency. But this really isn't in the same ballpark as e.g. raising KeyError consistently in APIs."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-08-02 21:46:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Just throwing my +1 in here. The consensus was "either way is fine." Not "We aren't doing periods anymore."

Also, I dislike the check on commit at this level also because it requires running flake8/hacking/w'ever after commit.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-08-02 22:32:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I'm also +1 on this one.  for the reasons above. 

not +2 on this because I don't feel very strongly either way and don't want to have this go in with any -1's attached."}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2013-08-02 22:44:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Well, the only negative vote is Mark's -2, so it won't merge unless he rescinds it anyway.

I personally have started trying to break myself of the habit of adding a full stop at the end of a commit title in agreement with the various arguments made to that effect, but still also agree that actual enforcement of this is well beyond arbitrary."}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2013-08-02 22:49:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I also would not be adverse to seeing this check brought back as an opt-in for projects, but that would require an additional feature in hacking to allow inclusion of specific optional non-default-enforced nit picking rules.'}, {'account_id': 6786, 'date': '2013-08-03 06:30:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I think that it could be configurable, my change request with conf helper has been merged, so, we can add the conf to enforce period at the end of title line.'}, {'account_id': 6786, 'date': '2013-08-03 06:56:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Here it is - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/40050/'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2013-08-08 12:47:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Mark - I think what's changed since last time for me is that it's become clear that the mechanics of enforcement are producing stress and strain. If the process is: write code, run tox, commit, git review - which is a common one - then the dev does not get feedback about the violation until submitting the code. That doesn't seem like a fair check. In fact, if we really want to get specific about commit messages, gerrit does commit message checking and can spit out warnings about them. I had a patch in gerrit a while ago that we stopped caring about that would prevent the upload if the commit message didn't match. Rather than letting people upload things, then having the gate run 10 devstack tests only to find out that they have a period or a bug mention in a title - how about we stop checking commit messages in hacking and if we want to enforce rules we do it gerrit side?"}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-08-08 17:21:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Monty, ++ for moving all git checks out of hacking into git-review and/or gerrit. I agree doing git checks here is a ugly hack'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-08-08 23:06:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

What a ridiculous bunch of people we are. Me included.

I don't buy the description of consensus from the previous discussion - my read of the consensus was "no period is the right way, but we're losers for wasting time debating this"

One point in the thread does it for me - http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-June/010870.html - i.e. the guy who went to the bother of documenting in huge detail the best practice for git commit messages, and whose recommendations the project has accepted with pretty much no debate, says "of course you shouldn't terminate with a period, duh". If wiki pages had maintainers, Dan would be the maintainer of this one and I'm pretty sure he'd be vehemently against adding any text which suggests terminating with a period is acceptable practice.

Again, a reminder of how all this started - a patch of mine to diskimage-builder was -1ed based on project policy until I added a period to the first line. As soon as someone wastes developers time by -1ing patches for this kind of stuff, we always say it's best to agree on a style and enforce it. That's what we're doing here.

On removing git commit message checks from hacking altogether - that's a debate for a patch which removes all of them from hacking. I actually hate gerrit grumping about commit messages and think the way we have been enforcing this has been working out fine.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-08-08 23:26:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

As I read the discussion there was a roughly 50/50 split about correctness and about 80/20 on the 'why are we talking about this', and about 80/20 on this shouldn't even be a thing.

The pattern of 'where there is debate pick something and make it a hard rule' is a bad pattern - yes it is what OpenStack has been doing, but as Chris Armstrong put most eloquently, it's not the only way. You can *also* say 'this thing does not make the project better or worse, do not hold back +2's on it'.

Thats what we're now doing in TripleO on period's in commit title lines : like it or not some folk have grammar built into their muscle memory from decades of using different VCS systems [and the period statistics from OpenStack projects demonstrates that].

How does this particular rule help the project? The only reason it's in hacking at all is because it was added here as a -reaction- to my enforcing something that the project has decided doesn't matter."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-16 06:03:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-16 06:03:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2013-06-26 19:16:19.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Add check for end of title line of commit messages"

There does not appear to be strong consensus for or against this, so
hacking should not enforce it.  If an individual project wishes to

commit_message:
Revert "Add check for end of title line of commit messages"

There does not appear to be strong consensus for or against this, so
hacking should not enforce it.  If an individual project wishes to
enforce this they can do so in a local check.

This reverts commit da408d997d90816ae09111ca3c6d391d29ac8402.

Change-Id: I9cd565d39b6a6da6c8397f27073d15c378155179

[{'created': '2013-07-28 06:07:09.000000000', 'message': "Refactor Huawei iscsi driver to better use SSHPool

In previous code, Huawei iscsi driver does a lot of tricks on code
to support auto-switching controller when failed. For example, they
changed the server_ip of a SSHPool during runtime; They use SSHPool.get()
instead of SSHPool.item(), which is not suggest to use after Python 2.5

In this patch, I refactor the code in a cleaner way, including:
    1. Allocating two seperate pools , one for each controller
        During failure, we just need to switch the pool we use, no need
        to lock the pool and changing the ip of a existing pool

    2. Use SSHPool.item() instead of SSHPool.get()
        Per suggested by Eventlet, refer to
        https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/blob/master/eventlet/pools.py#L64

    3. Cleanup the SSHConn.create()
        Since we don't need to manually close a client, it's OK for us to
        use the infinite socket timeout, so just use the create() method
        in SSHPool

    4. Cleanup unused function in utils.py

        SSHPool.remove() is created and used only by Huawei driver, it's
        bugly(fixed in grizzly but not in master), since we don't need it,
        just remove it.

        utils.create_channel is also created and only used by this driver,
        it could be replace by client.invoke_shell(width=XX, height=XX)

Change-Id: Id21cb677d041af3c9ba414fefcb0f6ac6bca0f3a

commit_message:
Refactor Huawei iscsi driver to better use SSHPool

In previous code, Huawei iscsi driver does a lot of tricks on code
to support auto-switching controller when failed. For example, they
changed the server_ip of a SSHPool during runtime; They use
SSHPool.get() instead of SSHPool.item(), which is not suggest to use
after Python 2.5

In this patch, I refactor the code in a cleaner way, including:
    1. Allocating two seperate pools , one for each controller
        During failure, we just need to switch the pool we use, no
        need to lock the pool and changing the ip of a existing pool

    2. Use SSHPool.item() instead of SSHPool.get()
        Per suggested by Eventlet, refer to
        https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/blob/master/eventlet/
        pools.py#L64

    3. Cleanup the SSHConn.create()
        Since we don't need to manually close a client, it's OK for
        us to use the infinite socket timeout, so just use the
        create() method in SSHPool

    4. Cleanup unused function in utils.py

        SSHPool.remove() is created and used only by Huawei driver,
        it's bugly(fixed in grizzly but not in master), since we
        don't need it anymore, just remove it.
        (refer to https://review.openstack.org/#/c/28545/
         and https://review.openstack.org/#/c/26059/)

        utils.create_channel is also created and only used by this
        driver,it could be replace by
        client.invoke_shell(width=XX, height=XX)

Change-Id: Id21cb677d041af3c9ba414fefcb0f6ac6bca0f3a

update exception classes to inherit from common

common library.  The change provides a compatibility property since the
status_code attribute is called code in the common version.

commit_message:
Stop resetting logging on every call to __main__.

__main__ is called directly during tests, but was resetting the
logging environment within it, which prevented tests from capturing
the log events.

Change-Id: If710e11091723144c97c88aab4aa5e6126844d2b

Stop using tearDown.

be used.

commit_message:
Do not cache new data if command fails

The point of delaying the commit of data to the cache is that we want to
make sure the command succeeds before giving up on the data changes.
This will ensure that we keep trying the command with any given change
to the metadata until it succeeds.

Change-Id: Idf3a09686b4bbf0e16a9bc9f3359ee9937fcc627

commit_message:
Document the last file presence.

Smart hooks may want to perform delta analysis on metadata, and tests
want to be able to tell if the cache is updated it's previous state,
so we should make the presence and name of the old versions of the
files a stable interface.

Change-Id: Ia29c1ef9e10308d6461dae7823c5f497f6b90122

prepared for that.

commit_message:
Refactor Nexenta driver

Moving NEXENTA_OPTIONS out of nexenta/volume.py and splitting the
options. This change is to avoid duplication as the iSCSI and NFS driver
will use the same configuration options.

Change-Id: I3596fec9e852f07aea2ef7f2cd26023de07e7d0b

commit_message:
refactor/unify driver version strings

This patch updates each driver to provide
the same mechanism for reporting the version
of the driver.  It also includes fixing the
reported driver version at get_volume_stats()
time to be the version set in the driver.

When the manager starts the driver it now
logs the driver's name and version in the log file.

fixes Bug #1212878

Change-Id: Icefd065f885ad417735490e6ac90e2b21557d2dc

commit_message:
Handle missing cyper_type and algorithm fields

When creating orders, Http 500 responses would occurr when
these fields were missing because islower() would be called
on a None type.

Change-Id: I7d1b8c71a84f1fe9d8d33f1677b358eebc888484
Fixes: bug #1210583

I am concerned with the lack of consistency in use of punctuation in the messages.  You end some of the messages with a '.' and not others.  It looks like the existing 'Volume type not found.' messages do end with a '.'.  I would recommend changing the messages you are adding to do the same thing for consistency."}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-07-10 20:15:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-07-10 20:23:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi Jay,

Good catch thanks. I had _(externalized) the string 'Volume not found.' as-is thinking that I wanted to preserve the original string to prevent affecting its translation, but that was not necessary since it was not being translated in the 1st place because it was not _(externalized)  :)

I decided to remove the . from the end, since that is what the convention most of the other error messages in cinder and other components have done. In other words, the period at the end seems to be the exception, not the rule.

Thank you,"}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2013-07-10 20:35:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

You are right.  It does appear that the rule is to not end in a period.  I am a fan of punctuation, but it is important to be consistent.  :-)  So, I agree with the solution.  Thanks for addressing the issue.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-10 22:35:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Externalize error messages in the v2 API

This patch does more internationalization for the REST API error
messages that don't currently have it to take advantage of the new
support added by bp user-locale-api to show error messages in the locale
requested by the user through the Accept-Language HTTP header.

We only do v2 because consumers have used the response error message in
the past for error checks, so changing it in v1 too would break them.

Partially implements bp user-locale-api

Change-Id: I92780b42c125a91ab4916b7a31e4b71d306a89a1

commit_message:
Migrate nova-compute-instance to split Metadata.

The file was using the old 0.0.0.0 method from heat-localip, but it was
missed when converting the other templates to a split Metadata approach
to enable a machine to know its own IP.

Change-Id: I0b117de12416a52950b1c7079f659df8649d67f9

commit_message:
Add unit test to check non-string password support

Non-string passwords from keystoneclient are converted but
we are not testing it so adding in a test case for this.

Co-authored-by: r-sekine <r-sekine@intellilink.co.jp>
Fixes: bug #1210099

commit_message:
Adds support for passing extra tenant attributes to keystone

Patch adds simple kwargs parsing to tenant update and create
methods allowing users to exercise the extras functionality
of keystone.

As-per keystone data model docs:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/keystone/architecture.html#data-model

Change-Id: I1c375c70a0ab4519626d2238d65fa0695f953dc5
Fixes: bug #1180317

commit_message:
Added functions for get a ip on an instance

The cause of some gating failure looks like
because of getting ip address on instance.
However current exercise didn't log the return value.
In this commit, we add get_instance_ip function with
error hanlding support, and apply it on the execise.

Change-Id: I8e17ba68093faafe58a98eb780a032368eea38aa

While resizing a improper volume, it may stuck in "RESIZE" status and Trove
can't deal with this status with other actions. We need to catch the exception.

Now, resize volume method exists some problems to achieve the goal. This patch
will solve the critical problem firstly.

commit_message:
Fix resize volume stuck in "RESIZE" status

While resizing a improper volume, it may stuck in "RESIZE" status and Trove
can't deal with this status with other actions. We need to catch the exception.

Now, resize volume method exists some problems to achieve the goal. This patch
will solve the critical problem firstly.

fix bug 1212767
Change-Id: I868694fc01217ef0e6e8450ce981c4cab544b612

commit_message:
Set wsgi startup log level to INFO

Sets wsgi startup log to INFO so that it is
still visible when log level is raised above
DEBUG.

Co-authored-by: Kanami Akama <k-akama@intellilink.co.jp>
Fixes: bug #1208778

Change-Id: I977f4ac6fc5e11710922dc607d5ce23a0cc74237

commit_message:
Replace using tests.utils with openstack.common.test

It is the first step to replace using tests.utils with openstack.common.test.
All these tests don't use mock objects, stubs, config files and use only
BaseTestCase class.

Change-Id: I511816b5c9e6c5c34ebff199296ee4fc8b84c672

Increase length of username in DB

Fixes bug #1081932

commit_message:
File movement.

In order to rework some of the persistence layer I would
like to move around some of the files first, keeping job
specifics in a jobs folder. Having some of the items which
are root level taskflow items (flow, task) be at the root
of the hiearchy.

commit_message:
Ignore node not found error

This ignores errors if the machine can't be found in the database.
This is to ease the transition to nodepool.

Change-Id: I3f3a1b8804e48f5a8643971f003246aca413a866

commit_message:
Object Store: Set default wsgi workers to cpu_count

Patch Ifa563d22952c902ab8cbe1d339ba385413c54e95 introduces the option
"auto" for workers and also changes max_clients location in the sample files.

The documentation for workers was updated and for max_clients added.

Closes-Bug: #1200484

There were several methods overridden from the base virt driver class in
the powervm driver but all they did was pass which can cause problems
with tempest, e.g. the tempest test for pausing an instance will timeout

commit_message:
Clean up unimplemented methods in the powervm driver

There were several methods overridden from the base virt driver class in
the powervm driver but all they did was pass which can cause problems
with tempest, e.g. the tempest test for pausing an instance will timeout
waiting for the instance state to change. This change raises
NotImplementedError rather than passes so that tempest will fail out
quickly when testing something that the powervm driver does not
implement.

Also removes the overridden manage_image_cache method since it didn't do
anything, which is exactly what the base class does.

Added unit tests to make sure that methods which should simply pass do
and that tests which should raise NotImplementedError do that also.

Fixes bug 1205066

Change-Id: Ieaf256a5c0f54804686318d6cbd5877a5003c9eb

commit_message:
Persistence adjustments.

Quite a few persistence adjustments that I would
like to get in after the initially landed.

1. Move some of the items which are not really
   generics back to the root folder (task, flow).
   I think these are better here for now until they
   are changed.
2. Move the storage persistence layer to a persistence
   folder and simplify the API around the saving of
   logbooks, flowdetails and taskdetails so that the
   entrypoint for doing all this work is just via a
   logbook.
   a. This avoids the race conditions around
      mutating a taskdetail/flowdetail while that
      flowdetail/taskdetail is being used. Reducing the
      apis exposed that do saving/reading/loading reduces
      the consistency violations that have to be considered.
3. Move the backends that do persistence to persistence/
   backends instead of under the root backends/ folder.
4. Use the oslo db/sqlalchemy layer/migrate as much as possible
   instead of having a miniature version that we maintain ourselves.
5. Remove the celery backend for now to avoid confusion
   as that is being worked on and improved in
   review @ https://review.openstack.org/#/c/41972 anyway.

Change-Id: I5343dfdd6805f18ee59937bfcc92e6c768d49643

Currently, it is possible to auto-create groups by passing a group name
to register_opt or register_opts. However, it is not possible to
auto-register groups when a OptGroup instance is passed instead.

This patch adds support for that to the _get_group method. There are

commit_message:
Add auto-create support for OptGroup instances

Currently, it is possible to auto-create groups by passing a group name
to register_opt or register_opts. However, it is not possible to
auto-register groups when a OptGroup instance is passed instead.

This patch adds support for that to the _get_group method. There are
some advantages introduced by this patch:

    * It keeps consistency of oslo.config's public API.
    * It allow users to auto-register a group a group and
    re-use the instance:
        group = cfg.OptGroup("test")
        cfg.register_opts(..., group=group)
        # do something with the group
    * It allows users to auto-register groups with descriptions.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I9b9a74688c906d6bdea9c42044b47dc52e48c19d

commit_message:
install the common package in the common recipe

This fixes a bug on SUSE where the openstack-cinder (common) package
would not be installed when the template in recipes/cinder-common.rb is
created. That package requires the openstack-cinder user which is
created by the openstack-cinder package.

Change-Id: I745d5d32cc70bd2660a734821a682900f3d1043d

commit_message:
Fix handling of None, etc. replies

A rather embarassing and obvious bug - we're currently not allowing
endpoint methods to send replies of None, '', False, [], {}, etc.

Change-Id: Ifc5ff8f308f526197559a4df7bed244cff6ed3c1

commit_message:
Refactor Keystone to use unified logging from Oslo

Modifications to use log from /keystone/openstack/common/log.py instead
of /keystone/common/logging.py. This change also includes some
refactoring to remove the WriteableLogger class from common/wsgi.py
since that is already included in the unified logging sync from Oslo.
This also moves fail_gracefully from /keystone/common/logging.py to
service.py as it is only used within that module.

blueprint unified-logging-in-keystone

Change-Id: I24b319bd6cfe5e345ea903196188f2394f4ef102

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-07-25 08:11:59.000000000', 'message': "Modify message when l3-agent-scheduler fails.

Since you can only attach a single l3 agent to a router, when you try
to add another l3 agent to a router that already have one, the l3
agent scheduler raises an exception.

This fix modifies the message error saying explicitly that's because
another agent is already assigned.

Change-Id: If832bbd4bf17e4e0c4720172aded4c9fffedc6fc
Fixes: bug #1154622
"}, {'created': '2013-07-29 16:01:42.000000000', 'message': 'Modify message when l3-agent-scheduler fails.

Since you can only attach a single l3 agent to a router, when you try
to add another l3 agent to a router that already have one, the l3
agent scheduler raises an exception.

This fix removes the discrimination by id: either it is the same agent
or another one, the router can not be hosted and the same exception is
raised.

Change-Id: If832bbd4bf17e4e0c4720172aded4c9fffedc6fc
Fixes: bug #1154622
'}, {'created': '2013-07-29 17:49:41.000000000', 'message': 'Modify message when l3-agent-scheduler fails.

commit_message:
Unify exception thrown in l3-agent-scheduler fails

Since you can only attach a single l3 agent to a router, when you try
to add another l3 agent to a router that already have one, the l3
agent scheduler raises an exception.

This fix removes the discrimination by id: either it is the same agent
or another one, the router can not be hosted and the same exception is
raised.

Change-Id: If832bbd4bf17e4e0c4720172aded4c9fffedc6fc
Fixes: bug #1154622

commit_message:
Remove long db transaction for metadata access network

Bug 1204277

Removes nested transactions wrapping plugin ops, and adds
rollback code where required.
Also ensures NeutronPlugin.py does not attempt to remove router
ports twice.

Change-Id: I299d4ed688a70b6dff506c999355661cf783ae26

commit_message:
Do not call remove_router_lport in remove_router_interface

Bug 1211149

The call will cause a failure as the router port is already removed
by _nvp_delete_router_port.
This patch also add the support on the fake nvp api client to verify
this kind of condition.

Change-Id: Ieb5ca5c239ccc993b96dd5bad0b412211b45417e

commit_message:
Remove old legacy network info model in libvirt driver

Update libvirt driver, virt firewall and hypervisor unit tests to
use nova.network.model instead of legacy "network,mapping" tuple.

Partly implement blueprint nova-network-legacy

Co-author: Amir Sadoughi<amir.sadoughi@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I4d38bb81a4f64efdb78f5da52fbbb382981e0b96

Agree with Mathieu. If this package is needed by nova-network, please move it to puppet-nova.
puppet-openstack is designed to make better use of 'lower' modules, it does't handle package dependency."}, {'account_id': 7156, 'date': '2013-08-06 23:43:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Yu, it's already in puppet-nova.

My concern is that nova::compute would now be aware of which network implementation is used which I feel shouldn't be the case.

By moving it to nova::network, it would make nova::compute agnostic of the network implementation.

However Emilien tells me that with the use of nova-network in single-node setup, although only the network node runs nova-network (configured by nova::network), the compute node would still require the installation of bridge-utils.

Moving bridge-utils to nova::network would therefore not be an option for this particular deployment setup."}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2013-08-07 07:36:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Let me explain you nova-network again and demonstrate that nova-compute needs to know which network manager we use.

In nova-network we have 2 modes:
* multi-host, where nova-network runs on each compute nodes. In this case, I agree bridge utils could be managed by nova::network.
* single host, where nova-network run on a dedicated node (usually the controller), and then you should install bridge-utils on all compute nodes. That's why the bridge-utils stuff should be defined on nova::compute, since this is a dependency when we use both modes in nova-network.

Thank's for reconsiderating the review."}, {'account_id': 1607, 'date': '2013-08-07 07:54:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Emilien, I get your idea now. 
In single host mode, compute nodes still need bridge-utils, that's the reason why this package should be in nova::compute. 
Sorry for misunderstanding your intention."}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2013-08-07 08:01:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

No worries at all, it's a bit complicated to do something clean.

Let's continue the reviews to check that everybody is agree with this point of view.

commit_message:
Install bridge-utils only if needed

The package bridge-utils is useful only if we have nova-network.
If we use Neutron, we don't have to install it.

This patch provides a condition "neutron_enabled" to check before the
installation of the package.

Fix bug #1176087

commit_message:
Add support for CA authentication in Keystone

* Add os_cacert flag support in manifests
* Add all required tests for Agent Central

Patch in Ceilometer: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/38448/

Change-Id: I6689143daddfac71ca5dcc2c6fd55cd14a4455e3

commit_message:
Allow mapping _ to lazy gettext path

Since nova has switched from using gettext.install for
importing the _ function to explicitly importing the _
function from gettextutils, we need to be able to enable
our deferred translation code path on the gettextutils._
function.

Change-Id: I7fec00810ea57c985e1f43c644913a9980b35655

Well, that doesn't cut it - if there is really no other reason for keeping run_tests.sh around other than "it's what people are used to running", we should replace it with a script which just does 'please run tox'

I suspect Joe knows of valid reasons why we haven't done it yet, though'}, {'account_id': 7491, 'date': '2013-06-17 12:13:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Hi All. Thanks for review.

The problem with tox is that it creates a source distribution every time. It takes ~10 seconds on my PC.
It is ok, if you run all tests, but annoying, if you run a single test.

Also in tox at the moment:
- there is no possibility to run tests with testtools instead of testr. This feature allows us to use the debugger.
- in some projects tox doesn't use a testr wrapper to report progress while tests are running"}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2013-06-17 12:14:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Victor +1'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2013-06-17 22:36:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

So, I'm SUPER torn on this.

On the one hand, we use tox in the gate, and run_tests.sh hides that from people and then they get confused about why some change they made to run_tests.sh doesn't get reflected in the reality of the project.

On the other hand, what Victor says is true. We need to land a couple of changes to upstream tox that would allow it to not run develop each time - but we seem to have a hard time doing that.

On the third hand, we'd doing an INSANE amount of work to make working with testing in a venv "easy" and what we've wound up with is a situation where we have multiple competing incompatible ways of doing things.

Here's what I do:
source .tox/py27/bin/activate
testr run --parallel
testr run --parallel
testr run some-test
testr run --failing
deactivate

Sometimes, if I'm being fancy, I'll do:
virtualenv foo
foo/bin/pip install -r requirements.txt -r test-requirements.txt

I believe vish just installs the depends directly on his box and skips venvs altogether.

It turns out that testr is a powerful tool with a nice UI. Instead of putting wrappers around it, perhaps we should add support for our output stream thing we like to it upstream. We should also add support to it for dropping into a debugger directly, so that the testtools issue goes away. Then we should land a patch to upstream tox to get it to do setup.py develop instead of sdist+ install.

If we did that, we could have "run tox" be the simple answer for anyone who just wants to run whatever the gate runs, because that will always work. And if they want to do fancier things, they should learn about venvs and testr.

However, if we ARE going to keep a run_tests.sh file in our trees, we should certainly have a single copy and have it behave consistently.

Please note that some projects actually do just have run_tests.sh as a thin wrapper around tox.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-06-17 22:39:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

As for the sdist part, on my machine 

`$ time tox -epy27 --sdistonly` takes 3 seconds real time for me


If I remember correctly these were some of the  pros and cons for run_tests.sh:


Cons:
- holds developers hands too much, we should be showing them how to learn the underlying tools

Pros: 
- Provides a way to run tests outside of a virtualenv (can be very useful)
- Runs tests in a manor to generate pretty output


given that, it seems like there is a reason to keep something around (show people how to run tests with pretty output, no virtualenv etc), but we should promote people to  use the underlying tools whenever possible (to learn how python and OpenStack actually do things). For example there is no reason to use run_tests.sh for pep8/flake8 checks.  those can be trigged via 'tox -epep8' or just run flake8 by hand (assuming you have hacking installed).  Perhaps run_tests.sh should be turned into a run_tests readme file instead."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-06-17 23:09:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Move `./run_tests.sh` to Oslo

Moved Nova `./run_tests.sh` script to `tools/run_tests_common.sh` file.
This script run unit-tests and can be reused in other projects.
Added script `./run_tests.sh` with project specific variables to run
`tools/run_tests_common.sh` script.
Added required `tools/*` files for pretty colorizer outpoot.
Modified `tests/utils.py` file - added work with OS_TEST_TIMEOUT,
OS_STDOUT_CAPTURE and OS_STDERR_CAPTURE environment variables from .testr.conf

blueprint run-tests-script

Change-Id: I057e8cf2c74d160402cb881fc761623c74905b7e

occurring in Enforcer._get_policy_path

commit_message:
Revoke user tokens when disabling/delete a project

- Revoke tokens scoped to all users from a project when disabling or
  deleting the project.
- Tests provided by Dolph.

Closes-Bug: #1179955
Change-Id: I8ab4713d513b26ced6c37ed026cec9e2df78a5e9
Signed-off-by: Chmouel Boudjnah <chmouel@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Fix test_user_enable_attribute_mask so it actually tests

test_user_enable_attribute_mask wasn't actually testing
user_enable_attribute_mask because it didn't reload the backend
after changing the config value.

Change-Id: I9fa6bebe0c4b3d2afc1eb53867cf217b046b0210
Related-Bug: #1210175

[{'created': '2013-08-15 16:35:12.000000000', 'message': "Don't wait for ack when deleting expired messages

This patch simply sets write concern to 0 in the MongoDB driver,
when removing expired messages. This shortens the amount of time
that garbage collection takes, and slightly reduces the amount
of traffic going between app and db servers, as well as between
master and secondary nodes.

This is a safe thing to do, since the operator will be running
multiple GC daemons, so that in the case of a failure, the
operation will be retried in the near future.

The downside is that persistent failures to collect expired
messages will cause the DB to grow out of control; however,
it is expected that if this operation is failing, more than
likely message CRUD in general is failing, which mitigates
the risk just mentioned.

Change-Id: I90950721361dacffa508624281d2e2ea8cf53724
"}]
commit_message:
Don't wait for ack when deleting expired messages

This patch simply sets write concern to 0 in the MongoDB driver,
when removing expired messages. This shortens the amount of time
that garbage collection takes, and slightly reduces the amount
of traffic going between app and db servers, as well as between
master and secondary nodes.

This is a safe thing to do, since the operator will be running
multiple GC daemons, so that in the case of a failure, the
operation will be retried in the near future.

The downside is that persistent failures to collect expired
messages will cause the DB to grow out of control; however,
it is expected that if this operation is failing, more than
likely message CRUD in general is failing, which mitigates
the risk just mentioned.

Change-Id: I90950721361dacffa508624281d2e2ea8cf53724

[{'created': '2013-08-14 23:04:46.000000000', 'message': 'Use req.get_param's store feature in lieu of utils.purge

This patch removes the use of utils.purge since it is no
longer needed in light of Falcon's relatively new "store"
feature, which causes the target dict to only receive the
value of the param if it is found in the request, thus
avoiding clobbering default kwarg values, which was the
original intent of utils.purge.

As a bonus, this approach is also ~40% faster.

Note: Also in this patch is a modification to reduce GC
latency by not waiting for an ack from MongoDB when erasing messages.

Change-Id: I6b3d82b1f700045e50b3131902b2c7b6dc6ea13c
Implements: blueprint v1-obvious-optimizations

commit_message:
Use req.get_param's store feature in lieu of utils.purge

This patch removes the use of utils.purge since it is no
longer needed in light of Falcon's relatively new "store"
feature, which causes the target dict to only receive the
value of the param if it is found in the request, thus
avoiding clobbering default kwarg values, which was the
original intent of utils.purge.

As a bonus, this approach is also ~40% faster.

Change-Id: I6b3d82b1f700045e50b3131902b2c7b6dc6ea13c
Implements: blueprint v1-obvious-optimizations

commit_message:
Reverse default order of collectors.

The default order results in less-dynamic heat_local and ec2 overriding
the more dynamic cfn source. That is the opposite of what is desired.

Change-Id: I7e1feb2e6869b4f076200668dd204219ecc4224e

commit_message:
Add check for deprecated method assertEquals

The proper one is assertEqual, assertEquals is deprecated as of 2.7.
Of course, remembering which one is good and which one is bad is
absolutely impossible.

Change-Id: I79c5417ea2d11091ed7d73cf28c534feef6f7ba9

commit_message:
Use apiclient library from oslo

This library can be used in novaclient, keystoneclient,
glanceclient, and other client projects. The library
contains common code and uses python-requests for
HTTP communication.

Features:
* reissue authentication request for expired tokens;
* pluggable authentication;
* rich exceptions hierarchy.

Partially implements: blueprint common-client-library

Change-Id: Ieb25a32115d170cb78b5ef3d7da7dd9312c17a20

commit_message:
Use exceptions from oslo

The new apiclient.exceptions hierarchy is more comprehensive
and it covers almost all HTTP error status codes. These
exceptions can be used in novaclient, keystoneclient,
glanceclient, and other client projects thus providing a
single inteface. When apiclient.exceptions will be released
as a library, users can have benefit from OpenStack clients
raising exceptions of known classes while now every client has
its own classes making difficult to catch, e.g., NotFound for
every client.

Partially implements: blueprint common-client-library

Change-Id: I6f09fdee4222e6000f93bceeda3adf39ac4edddc

commit_message:
Make compute_capabilities_filter use information from DB not RPC

Make compute_capabilities_filter directly use the data in host_state and
not the data capabilities data that is currently broadcast from the
schedulers over RPC, as this will be removed since it doesn't scale.

The filter name, compute_capabilities_filter, is kept the same to keep
backwards compatibility.

Once all the capabilities usage in scheduler filters is removed, the
capabilities RPC broadcast can be removed.

Part of bp no-compute-fanout-to-scheduler.

Change-Id: I846259b363a794803e230eaf25c69c52970b6c4f

commit_message:
Make affinity_filters use host_ip from DB not RPC

Instead of using host_ip from capabilities, which are being removed, get the
host_ip from the same place the rest of scheduling information comes
from, the database.

Part of bp no-compute-fanout-to-scheduler

Change-Id: I56a1cbb1903c20b347469d0ee5a8c6d89a21c44e

commit_message:
db: Add host_ip and supported_instances to compute_nodes

In order to remove compute capabilities being broadcast via RPC to the
schedulers, host_ip and supported_instances, the two pieces of data the
scheduler uses that aren't in the database today, need to be added.
In the scope of this blueprint, only the way the filters are getting
their data is changed, not how the data is generated or anything else.

host_ip is used by the affinity_filter and supported_instances is used
by image_props_filter.

Part of bp no-compute-fanout-to-scheduler

Change-Id: I72371260159c9fdffcdb57209095fc103b6dd79e

commit_message:
Remove the mongo auth warning during tests

pymongo print a warning on each mongodb connection because the url used
in tests don't have credentials, since all mongodb tests are running in
a different mongodb databases, this print many annoying line like this one:

UserWarning: database name or authSource in URI is being ignored. If you
wish to authenticate to ceilometer_90d94586954643e8811d5ecc6bacf912, you
must provide a username and password.

This change suppress this line during testing.

Fixes bug #1210674

Change-Id: Iecabca621c2fbaf15e644f2fca66b4e3b5bd04e7

commit_message:
Import missing gettext _

All ceilometer service/agent use gettextutils.install but
gettext method _ is not even installed for test.

This change, import gettext method _ explicitly in each file
that use _ .

Change-Id: Ic30e301f420a4626c3b8725aa450cd7638ece3fe

commit_message:
Adding extra_specs to flavor format

We have added a new API extension FlavorWithExtraSpecs which when
enabled, will add the extra_specs of a flavor to the flavor
show and detail calls.
This handles the extra_specs field while parsing the flavor response
in the _format_flavor method.

Implements blueprint add-extra-specs-to-flavor-format

Change-Id: I46faaab69381c07b4c1466188a9c23014d869418

commit_message:
Extract ISCSI tries option into connector module

The usage of this option occurred only in that module.
Rename this options to num_volume_device_scan_tries,
according to discussion on IRC.
The old one marked as depricated option.

DocImpact
Change-Id: Ib4a37237c2d95ca2dd6c05ce0a41f930b29ffd1c

[{'created': '2013-08-14 00:59:43.000000000', 'message': "Improve Proxy Signing Directory Support

1. The signing_dir was being created on every swift node
when it's only needed on proxies:

  http://docs.openstack.org/grizzly/openstack-compute/install/apt/content/installing-and-configuring-the-proxy-node.html

2. The signing_dir was not configurable, even though
the OpenStack doc's show multiple references
(/var/cache/swift and /home/swift/keystone-signing).

Based off the following patch from master:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/40356/

Change-Id: I3eb00046fc535a32d7a1800d15489e9fe071373b
"}]
commit_message:
Improve Proxy Signing Directory Support

1. The signing_dir was being created on every swift node
when it's only needed on proxies:

  http://docs.openstack.org/grizzly/openstack-compute/install/apt/content/installing-and-configuring-the-proxy-node.html

2. The signing_dir was not configurable, even though
the OpenStack doc's show multiple references
(/var/cache/swift and /home/swift/keystone-signing).

Based off the following patch from master:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/40356/

Change-Id: I3eb00046fc535a32d7a1800d15489e9fe071373b

commit_message:
Adds Support for Managing the Token Driver Backend

Previously the keystone class did not manage the token driver.
High-Availability deployments of Keystone must use the SQL
driver so that all Keystone instances can access the same token
from a SQL database cluster.

The patch adds the token_driver parameter that is used to manage
the selection of the token driver backend in keystone.conf.
The parameter defaults to 'keystone.token.backends.kvs.Token' for
backwards compatibility and to use the KVS backend driver.

Change-Id: I4879052b7e44272c176814d048f916cb77d33581

commit_message:
Mock os.makdirs to avoid directory creation in unit tests

The directory 'dhcp' under neutron state path should not be
created during unit tests. This patch mocks up calls to
os.makedirs and ensures that methods that rely on it, like
_populate_network_cache, are mocked as well.

Fixes bug #1211952

Change-Id: I83998d4e631b1ebeab90b4c3c0276aa2ffe22c50

commit_message:
Store owner_id on Stack so updates maintain it

Instead of passing owner to the store() method of parser.Stack,
it is now maintained as an attribute of the Stack instance,
and store() will use that saved attribute when saving.

This fixes the problem of losing the owner_id on updates to
a stack.

Fixes bug 1212013

Change-Id: I1e3b7832291ca0f5cda24c1995ab782824e48943

This modification addresses Bug #1210296, specifically addressing

'}]
commit_message:
Fixing malformed assert message formatting

This modification addresses Bug #1210296, specifically addressing
malformed assert message formatting in assert_called_anytime. When
verifying that an API method was called during test execution, the
assert statement used will throw a TypeError when formatting the
assert message, instead of the expected AssertionError. This occurs
because a nested tuple in the format list is not properly expanded.
The error itself likely exists because assert_called_anytime is not
currently used in the python-cinderclient testing framework.

The fix involves joining the arguments in the format list into a
single tuple, allowing proper argument expansion.

Fixes: bug 1210296

Change-Id: I6cf9dd55cff318e8a850637c540436c91dac08df

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-06 06:21:43.000000000', 'message': "Fix Several Issues Related to the Proxy Signing Directory

1. The signing_dir was being created on every swift node
when it's only needed on proxies.

2. The signing_dir was not configurable, even though
the OpenStack doc's show multiple references
(/var/cache/swift and /home/swift/keystone-signing):

  http://docs.openstack.org/trunk/openstack-compute/install/yum/content/installing-and-configuring-the-proxy-node.html

3. The signing_dir permissions were being configured as
root:swift instead of swift:swift.  This caused the following
error and the inablity for the swift-proxy service to start:

proxy-server UNCAUGHT EXCEPTION#012Traceback
'signing_dir is not owned by %s' % os.getlogin

Change-Id: I3eb00046fc535a32d7a1800d15489e9fe071373b
"}, {'created': '2013-08-06 15:59:04.000000000', 'message': "Fix Several Issues Related to the Proxy Signing Directory

1. The signing_dir was being created on every swift node
when it's only needed on proxies.

2. The signing_dir was not configurable, even though
the OpenStack doc's show multiple references
(/var/cache/swift and /home/swift/keystone-signing):

  http://docs.openstack.org/trunk/openstack-compute/install/yum/content/installing-and-configuring-the-proxy-node.html

3. The signing_dir permissions were being configured as
root:swift instead of swift:swift.  This caused the following
error and the inablity for the swift-proxy service to start:

proxy-server UNCAUGHT EXCEPTION#012Traceback
'signing_dir is not owned by %s' % os.getlogin

Change-Id: I3eb00046fc535a32d7a1800d15489e9fe071373b
"}, {'created': '2013-08-06 23:00:56.000000000', 'message': "Fix Issues Related to Swift Proxy Signing Directory

1. The signing_dir no longer needs to be managed, as it is
dynamiclly created by the keystone client.

The default behavior of the authtoken middleware is sufficient.
It will create a temporary directory to store the certs.

Workaround for https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1154809

Example:

root@swiftproxy01:~# find / -name signing*
/tmp/keystone-signing-hDDwFf/signing_cert.pem

Previously, the swift-proxy service would start, but the
signing_dir permissions were being configured as
root:swift instead of swift:swift.  This caused the following
error and the inablity for the swift-proxy service to work
properly:

proxy-server UNCAUGHT EXCEPTION#012Traceback
'signing_dir is not owned by %s' % os.getlogin

When the permissions are changed to swift:swift, the proxy service
works but you receive errors when using service proxy-server to
manage the service.

Change-Id: I3eb00046fc535a32d7a1800d15489e9fe071373b
"}, {'created': '2013-08-12 18:39:16.000000000', 'message': "Improve Proxy Signing Directory Support

1. The signing_dir was being created on every swift node
when it's only needed on proxies:

  http://docs.openstack.org/grizzly/openstack-compute/install/apt/content/installing-and-configuring-the-proxy-node.html

2. The signing_dir was not configurable, even though
the OpenStack doc's show multiple references
(/var/cache/swift and /home/swift/keystone-signing).

Change-Id: I3eb00046fc535a32d7a1800d15489e9fe071373b
"}]
commit_message:
Improve Proxy Signing Directory Support

1. The signing_dir was being created on every swift node
when it's only needed on proxies:

  http://docs.openstack.org/grizzly/openstack-compute/install/apt/content/installing-and-configuring-the-proxy-node.html

2. The signing_dir was not configurable, even though
the OpenStack doc's show multiple references
(/var/cache/swift and /home/swift/keystone-signing).

Change-Id: I3eb00046fc535a32d7a1800d15489e9fe071373b

commit_message:
Tolerate missing user on signal responder delete

SignalResponder delete fails if the created user
has already been deleted.

This change catches the 404 as for the User resource.

Change-Id: I55034469d10f2742296f0415fe26272d3683530d
Closes-bug: #1211633

commit_message:
add support for no response and failed request audit

when no response is given, set outcome to unknown
when request is not audited (req missing cadf_model), do audit on
response
add docstring to explain functions

Change-Id: I622ea05aae477b9897e0968d52faf60dbbc4f819

commit_message:
Fix order creation bug involving content types

Order creation was trying to look up mime_type, which is no longer
a supported field. MIME type was replaced with payload_content_type
and a secret_payload_content_type column was created. The database
must be flushed or the addition must be migrated for this to work
properly. Also require payload_content_type when creating orders.

Fixes: bug #1208528
Change-Id: I51e93ec63ce2786ddb7a47d528cc70507a7d88dd

commit_message:
Add supported_instances to get_available_resource to all virt drivers

Add 'supported_instances' to the function get_available_resource for all
virt drivers (except libvirt which is done separately). This will help
make image_props_filter work without the RPC broadcast capabilities.

Part of bp no-compute-fanout-to-scheduler

Change-Id: If9eee203b3cbb12963dc55e4215d206cb5d81264

Bob, I've had a bit more time to digest this, I understand it's basically just to get os_PACKAGE defined; as it stands there are a few loose ends I'd like to clean up.

Based on the string in GetOSVersion you'll wind up with:

 os_VENDOR=XenServer
 os_CODENAME=xenenterprise
 os_UPDATE=0-70446c
 os_RELEASE=6.2
 os_PACKAGE=rpm

Then GetDistro will produce:

 DISTRO=XenServer-6.2.0-70446c

I think this needs to be cleaned up a bit to be more useful.  Simply adding 

 "$os_VENDOR" =~ (XenServer)

to the existing Red Hat/CentOS check will produce:

 DISTRO=rhel6

which may or may not be a good thing.  Alternatively, an additional elif block specific to XenServer would let you make it:

 DISTRO=xen6
 DISTRO=xen6.2

or whatever.  I'd suggest 'xen6' if the minor release is used the same way it is in RHEL.


Also, please put a bit more of the reason for this in the commit message.  It's helpful when looking at things offline and LaunchPad bugs are not available.'}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-08-13 20:53:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-08-13 20:56:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Add XenServer to GetDistro's logic

This is primarily to satisfy the expectations of various scripts that os_*
variables are defined, and will result in a distro similar to "xs6.1.0-59235p"

Fixes bug 1211001

Change-Id: I951e1eb3a5e25f4d8773a11b15cf38157b6492fe

commit_message:
Adding HOT WordPress_NoKey sample

Adding WordPress_NoKey sample for F18 based on the same
CFN sample.
The HOT sample uses a new function str_replace to simplify the definition
of the instance init script. More cleanup can be done as soon as the
native compute instance resource becomes available.

Note: the new sample depends on change https://review.openstack.org/41461
in the heat github repository for processing the str_replace function.

Change-Id: Idc1986b0cca08d094079b83653967bba14d07a7b

commit_message:
Sped up tests by using smaller files

Switched one of the disk file tests to use a smaller file size for
testing. The larger size was not needed and accounted for ~3% of the
total test time by itself.

Change-Id: Ie71a390117baa2d286122a46880a4558f50b83b9

commit_message:
VMware: Add cinder support to devstack

The patch set adds cinder support to devstack. VMware cinder support
can be found at:
 - Nova - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/40245/
 - Cinder - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/41600/

commit_message:
No need to declare the exception conf

Brick can just assume that the conf entry exists
in each project that will use brick.
Cinder and Nova already declare the same exact
conf entry.

Change-Id: I4e0e11ce6f99a663a75e582ead92ac9d61300032

commit_message:
take care of books with sources in subdirectories

At the moment the validation doesn't take care of books
where the pom.xml is in an other directory than the sources
of the book. This patch will fix this issue.

For example: the pom.xml of basic-install is available at
doc/src/docbkx/basic-install/pom.xml but the sources of the
books are in doc/src/docbkx/basic-install/src. Because
the path to the pom.xml differs from the path of the sources
the validation will not check the files in the sources
directory for xi:include elements.

Change-Id: I3b92c3c4bff46ba6f9ac53b3ec56d24e7caf6ff6

commit_message:
added scripts to cleanup spaces in XML files

example for remove_trailing_whitespaces.sh:

"  testing   \n" --> "  testing\n"

examples for remove_unnecessary_spaces.py:

"<testing>    foobar foobar" --> "<testing>foobar foobar"
"foobar foobar   </testing>" --> "foobar foobar</testing>"

Change-Id: Ie15a7a1491bf412ff893c84e76061ef623581145

commit_message:
Switch smoker URL to ssl. Disable ssl validation.

Updates SmokeStack URL to be the SSL version.

Also, changes httplib2 so that we allow insecure SSL. This
is because we aren't using signed certificates with SmokeStack at the
moment.

Change-Id: I798c923efc07849be19521d7fc1730ca1e771838

commit_message:
Fix some logic in get_caching_iter

Mismatched indentation meant that more chunks than
expected could be yielded.

Make both filesystem ChunkedFile and S3 ChunkedFile
handle the case where the filepointer no longer exists.

Added unit tests which reproduced the problem
using both a filesystem and S3 ChunkedFile.

Fixes bug 1194929.

Change-Id: I0f70155e59f6bc754c88b5b9e96645459bfe770a

[{'created': '2013-08-15 02:08:40.000000000', 'message': "Replace os.unlink with delete_if_exists

Shouldn't care when doing unlink on our temp files
if they exist or not.  In fact this causes problems
when you do things like with tempfile/dir and happen
to try and unlink after it's already been removed.

This replaces these calls with the safer
common.fileutils.delete_if_exists which will
ignore the os exception of the object DNE.

Fixes bug: 1212502

Change-Id: Ica86c95f736411da486335aec5512e59247bfbc0
"}]
commit_message:
Replace os.unlink with delete_if_exists

Shouldn't care when doing unlink on our temp files
if they exist or not.  In fact this causes problems
when you do things like with tempfile/dir and happen
to try and unlink after it's already been removed.

This replaces these calls with the safer
common.fileutils.delete_if_exists which will
ignore the os exception of the object DNE.

Fixes bug: 1212502

Change-Id: Ica86c95f736411da486335aec5512e59247bfbc0

Thanks for working on this issue.   Unfortunately, I think you are missing something.  This patch only affects the 3par drivers and doesn't address the same issue in the base SanDriver code that has the same problems.

What we should be doing here is make a standalone method that both the 3par driver and the SanDriver can call to check ssh command arguments.   If we want to fix the security risk, then it needs to be applied in 1 place for all ssh code.

the _run_ssh call needs to be consistent between the 3par driver and the SanDriver in terms of arguments and their types.  You modified the 3par _run_ssh to accept a list instead of a string, but didn't change the SanDriver's _run_ssh to accept a list instead of a string.  There is also no checking in the SanDriver for it's arguments."}, {'account_id': 7593, 'date': '2013-07-27 03:07:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-27 04:13:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Works for me

commit_message:
Tidy up the SSH call to avoid injection attacks for HP's driver

Let the command and arguments form up a list and avoid the extra arguments
attackers inserted to the command string.

And modify the interface of _cli_run, there is no need for a extra argument.

fix bug 1192971
Change-Id: Iff6a3ecb64feccae1b29164117576cab9943200a

commit_message:
Fix bad check for openstack versions (vendor_data/config drive)

Looks like the lack of a test case sneaked in this bug. Added a
simple one that just ensures that we can get a list of all the
metadata information. Basic issue was that the check_version
was checking against ec2 versions. Changed it to check OpenStack
version including the 'latest'.

Fixes bug #1211122

Change-Id: Ifac7659467b81abcffd3f84a24292c11f2e058fc

commit_message:
setUpClass/tearDownClass full chain

Ensure the setUpClass/tearDownClass methods calls the super properly.
The setUpClass call tested at setUp time, the tearDownClass at exit
time.

super calling issues are also fixed.

Implements blueprint stop-leaking
Closes-Bug: #1212071

Change-Id: I266efe0cd363b330b1511e7e983dab9f62778848

commit_message:
libvirt: sync get_available_resources and get_host_stats

get_available_resources is actually used by the scheduler while
get_host_stats was previously used, and is still used for host
capabilities.  This patch makes get_available_resources and
get_host_stats use the same logic to clean up the code. As part of
making them use the same logic, some of the unused data returned from
get_host_stats is changed to be what get_available_resources expects.
This is also in preparation for removing the periodic RPC fanout from
compute nodes to the scheduler.

This patch cleans up libvirt and fake drivers only.  This is not needed
for other virt backends as this is a cleanup only.  Further cleanup of
libvirt and other drivers will happen after get_host_stats isn't used
for the compute fanout to schedulers.

Because this makes a change to the fake driver, several api samples
needed to be changed as well. The fake driver is changed so the
test_virt_driver tests can continue to be used

Part of bp no-compute-fanout-to-scheduler

Change-Id: I1eec5c117a1cb0490e9f9c09e731909bc31698a9

commit_message:
Correct os-collect-config.cfn.path to be string.

Specified as a list, it gets translated literally into
["NovaCompute0"] in /etc/os-collect-config.conf. This is not
desirable and results in 500 errors because ["NovaCompute0"] does
not exist.

Change-Id: I7dc01937d73c0c0e5cea70f5a3202d0e43c4caed

messages:
[{'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-07 17:17:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Build succeeded.

'}, {'account_id': 7555, 'date': '2013-08-07 17:42:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I don't want to have 'setenforce 0' in the image.

What if you used DIB's elements/selinux-permissive when building from Ubuntu or F18? The doc could change accordingly."}, {'account_id': 7732, 'date': '2013-08-08 08:44:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Did you test element 'selinux-permissive'? I can say that image with this element doesn't work as it needs for Savanna. I can't remember now what the problem was, but it doesn't work"}, {'account_id': 7555, 'date': '2013-08-08 16:38:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I've not tested selinux-permissive, primarily because I've never run into the selinux issue you have.

I just took a look at it though -

$ cat 11-selinux-permissive 
#!/bin/sh
echo "SELINUX=permissive" > /etc/selinux/config
echo "SELINUXTYPE=targeted" >> /etc/selinux/config

$ grep ^SELINUX /etc/selinux/config 
SELINUX=enforcing
SELINUXTYPE=targeted 

And I think it is probably broken for Fedora 19 (at least). It should use something like augtool to edit the config instead of assuming the contents of the file.

Please file a bug with DIB to get selinux-permissive fixed instead of working around it in savanna-extra.'}, {'account_id': 7732, 'date': '2013-08-13 14:26:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Problem with 'selinux-permissive' element was on F18, so I didn't use it on F19. Now, It works."}, {'account_id': 7732, 'date': '2013-08-13 14:26:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-13 14:27:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Support to use branches not merged yet.

Code style fixes.

Additional action 'upgrade' added. Now 'update' only fetches changes
from repo.

murano-git-install.sh now can fetch and install from branches that were
not merged yet. This should simplify testing and developing.

Change-Id: If10e830d46c8af58a26b242b576beaa66f8bc1b6

commit_message:
Raise exception when Glance metadata not found.

It'd be better to raise exception when trying to copy Glance metadata
from source (volume/snapshot) to destination (volume/snapshot) rather
than silent failure, which is exactly the reason there's unspotted error
inside glance_meta unittest but it was able to pass.
With this fix, one should _not_ directly call glance_metadata_copy()
without looking at source's bootable flags.  This patch also refactors
_create_volume_from_snapshot() and _create_from_source_volume() to only
do Glance metadata copy when needed (bootable is True).

Fix bug: 1211632

Change-Id: I28f065e21cf24c81f98b00e171fcbe4f64ec76b6

Please don't hate me.
I would like however to see db logic and rpc logic split - as we do for security groups.

Also, can you tell me why you decided to move from association on a router basis to global association for metering labels?

Those queries can become fairly expensive; and I'm still not sure what would happen if I create a label as a tenant (thus synchronizing labels for all tenants routers), and then do again the same operation as an admin, with different labels; the admin can see every tenant's routers - if you keep doing the query as you're doing now - and then perhaps the labels can be overwritten?"}, {'account_id': 7141, 'date': '2013-08-01 11:17:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21: (2 inline comments)

@Salvatore\xa0: first I don't hate you:), thanks for your reviews and your advices

I decided to move the association on a router to a association on tenant's routers because I want to be able to add metering rules to get traffic counters for a tenant. I want to be able to get traffic counters for a tenant (billing) even if a new router is spawned after that a metering label has been added.

commit_message:
Add metering extension and base class

This a part of the blueprint bandwidth-router-label

This patch initiates the blueprint by adding base class
to associate labels and metering rules to tenant's routers.

Change-Id: Ia93b49d881e79c3291730cff7b80f26c56fedb48

take a whole object as one of their parameters, even though all they need is

commit_message:
Conductor: only pass an ID to some methods

The following conductor methods:
    migration_update
    aggregate_host_add
    aggregate_host_delete
    aggregate_metadata_add
    aggregate_metadata_delete
    security_group_rule_get_by_security_group
    compute_node_update
    compute_node_delete
    service_update

take a whole object as one of their parameters, even though all they need is
its 'id' field. This patch addresses this issue by replacing the object with
its id in these methods.

A new method had to be added to the VirtAPI: aggregate_get(), that retrieves an
aggregate using its id.

This patch fixes bug #1204594.

Change-Id: I20237af7f27afdae47eef0e7fc56a87504442b77

commit_message:
Let OpenstackException.__str__ return string object

Having OpenstackException.__str__ not returning string object causes
problem when creating an error message by str(ex) where ex is an
object of OpenstackException.

Fixes bug #1208454

Change-Id: I5e06a95055017f28faa1f064f0db05f480d6effe

commit_message:
Convert Nova's virt driver to hypervisor plugins

This moves all of Nova's hypervisor (VIRT_DRIVER) configuation from
stack.sh to individual plugin files in lib/nova_plugins/hypervisor-*.
Adding support for a new hypervisor is now as simple as adding a new
plugin file.

The hypervisor image name and URL configuration in stackrc has been moved
into the plugin files; the variable names are changed around a bit to
set the defaults properly if nothing is set in the users localrc.
The names in localrc have not changed so this is all backward-compatible.

Rebased to support NUMBER_FAKE_NOVA_COMPUTE from https://review.openstack.org/39851

Change-Id: I83cfb620b1afb1ed7596827c2392bcd6c38b9f06

(1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-08-06 01:30:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-08-07 03:15:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Do not merge

Having a duplicate name will break templates using AWS::StackName and cfn tools using the CFN api like cfn-hup and cfn-init. Unique names per tenant seems like an assumption that needs to be protected or worked around.

Some thought needs to be given to those items before allowing this diversion from AWS. I am -2'ing until those thoughts have been communicated and any problems dealt with."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-08-07 15:01:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The alternative would be to actually enforce this restriction in the db so things like multi-engine or race conditions don't wind up in duplicate names anyway as is the case today. I'm not fussed about changing to that option, this just seemed to be the consensus at the time."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-08-07 17:07:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Right, I think this is something that we do need to do, as it makes everything simpler to scale.

However, we need to think hard about what to do here.

One thought is to add a way to get the stack ID in templates. We can encourage users to use that instead, and then make any CFN bits try the submitted name as a UUID query if it fails to find a stack by that name. Native Heat APIs and tools would work like all the other OpenStack APIs: names work unless there is a duplicate, UUID always works.

Also I don't think we can do something clever like make AWS::StackName return an ID instead. Stack name can be something meaningful to the deployment, and so I don't think we should tinker with it."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-08-07 22:51:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

You can use Ref: AWS::StackId to get the stack id in templates so I guess that's sorted. Ideas/pointers as to how to sort the other CFN bits appreciated as I'm just starting to dig into cfn-init/hup etc."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-08-08 00:35:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ah did not know about AWS::StackId. That does give us a fool proof recommendation then.

The problem is that we actually have a bug in the CFN API which prevents looking things up by StackId. There is code to look things up by an "ARN", but that appears to be a URL scheme, not the stack_id that would be returned from AWS::StackId.

So we either need to make AWS::StackId return the ARN, or make the CFN api treat name as "name or ID".'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-15 06:03:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-15 06:03:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}]

commit_message:
Allow multiple stacks with same name

Do not prevent a tenant from creating multiple stacks with the same name.
If we look up a stack by name and get multiple results, raise an error
similar to other openstack services.

fixes bug 1207043

Change-Id: I2577d835e2397243f180973709d87b2064915629
