By doing a substring-match on the repr() of the unittest.TestCase
during it's setUpClass, we can implement a generic way to skip tests
externally.

testtools gives a TestCase a unique id, so it's repr() looks like

<tempest.api.compute.admin.test_aggregates.AggregatesAdminTestJSON.test_aggregate_get_details_with_invalid_id[gate,negative] id=0x1bce5d0>

Thus by doing a sub-string match we can easily skip just a single test
case, or remove some parts of the suffix to skip entire ranges of
tests.

This is useful for someone using upstream tempest in an
continuous-integration situation where a failure is triaged as a local
issue, but a solution requires more work.  Although indiviual test
runners have options to skip, they may not always be as flexible as
one might like (e.g. [1]).  Having a generic and easily configured
method for users to skip in the config file is simple and
straight-forward.

[1] https://github.com/nose-devs/nose/pull/717

commit_message:
Generic skip interface

By doing a substring-match on the repr() of the unittest.TestCase
during it's setUpClass, we can implement a generic way to skip tests
externally.

testtools gives a TestCase a unique id, so it's repr() looks like

<tempest.api.compute.admin.test_aggregates.AggregatesAdminTestJSON.test_aggregate_get_details_with_invalid_id[gate,negative] id=0x1bce5d0>

Thus by doing a sub-string match we can easily skip just a single test
case, or remove some parts of the suffix to skip entire ranges of
tests.

This is useful for someone using upstream tempest in an
continuous-integration situation where a failure is triaged as a local
issue, but a solution requires more work.  Although indiviual test
runners have options to skip, they may not always be as flexible as
one might like (e.g. [1]).  Having a generic and easily configured
method for users to skip in the config file is simple and
straight-forward.

[1] https://github.com/nose-devs/nose/pull/717

Change-Id: If798c7f90f108cc53f42b991c88c47409b58d9e3

commit_message:
Extract failure reason before deleting nova server

If a nova server create fails, the server is deleted
leaving no indication of the source of the failure.

This change extracts the failure reason from the nova
server fault attribute and includes that in the raised
error.

Change-Id: I7a4618d9e3fded3cde1c15d5322b52eaf63a68f5

commit_message:
Don't double-restart nova-api.

Similar to glance, we used to poke at nova during in-instance setup
but that has been moved to API scripts from the deployer now, so we
don't need to force service availability before the rest of
os-refresh-config runs.

Change-Id: I83c9c53d8dcd38fba5bbfb603ca8d183a5efc63e

commit_message:
Don't double restart glance-* services.

The init-openstack script restarts glance services that are also
restarted by the glance elements os-refresh-config hooks. We don't
manipulate glance in-image now, so we can just wait for them to
restart post-configure.

Change-Id: I7bbac7b5103bf5196b7a05ee87d154a2558fb31d

commit_message:
Remove recommendation to use heat-localip.

Clint has fixed the heat templates to not suffer from the race
condition around IP address lookups, permitting us to no longer need
the heat-localip hack.

commit_message:
Remove heat-localip from devtest instructions.

With the recent changes to tripleo-heat-templates we no longer need to
use heat-localip to get the local IP of a machine. It is downloaded from
the Metadata in a secondary config object.

Fixes bug #1202322

commit_message:
Load local IP using separate post-boot Metadata.

Previously we could not feed the IP of an instance into its own
Metadata because of circular dependency problems. 0.0.0.0 was used
with the heat-localip element to work around this problem. This
caused problems though, as heat-localip would edit the source local
heat metadata, which would make cfn-hup and/or os-collect-config think
that the Metadata had changed, causing it to restart everything every
time we query the Metadata, which was about every five minutes.

Now we can just query this inert LaunchConfiguration resource to get
its' Metadata once it is ready. This resource will only change when
legitimate things are changed in the stack, and so we won't restart
everything every five minutes anymore. Note that when the native Heat
DSL lands, the OS::Heat::SoftwareConfig resource is meant for exactly
this purpose.

After this is merged we no longer need the heat-localip element.

Fixes bug #1202322

Change-Id: Id06323ba43203570eeebfa5b3d03fa56c16c0c10

commit_message:
Migrate from cfn-hup to os-collect-config

Os-collect-config is meant to replace cfn-hup from heat-cfntools. It
allows pulling from multiple metadata sources and runs continuously.

Fixes bug #1211289

Change-Id: Ia4e9127fb79048bd1022b32a37272f8463a774ae

commit_message:
Make Resource names suitable for merge/include

In nova-compute-instance.yaml, we need to use resource names that are
unique within the entire set of resources that may be merged or
included. However, we need the instance resource name to _match_ the
one in overcloud-source.yaml so that its own access policies can
function.

Without this change we will not have unique users and Metadata access
keys/policies for compute and controller.

Change-Id: Iebde7e6adede4984f4f693cf2d57b6fadb8be558

commit_message:
Migrate from cfn-hup to os-collect-config

Os-collect-config is meant to replace cfn-hup from heat-cfntools. It
allows pulling from multiple metadata sources and runs continuously.

Change-Id: I65e3b311f9d573446db38c74e9df0d26fe77e60f

commit_message:
Use separate Metadata to fetch self-IP

The instance cannot refer to its own IP without creating a circular
dependency. This way the instance boots with just the configuration for
os-collect-config, but then downloads the LaunchConfiguration for the
notcomputeConfig resource, which will include the IP for notcompute.

Fixes bug #1202322

Change-Id: I0a360a20741c6c705a3c814fa218b2c65950899f

test cases. So change the error message here that it can be captured.

commit_message:
Fix missing NovaComputeLibvirtType parameter.

Also change default to '' as null is not technically allowed as a
string default in cloudformation (Heat accidentally allows this).
Os-apply-config, via pystache, will still treat this as false for
the purposes of checking if it is set or not.

Change-Id: Ia02dbcf619bdc92647f1d21157fa4a8e3f749de3

commit_message:
Change test_post_alarm case in test_alarm_scenarios

It is not reasonable to assert that the new added object
will be the last one when call get_alarms, especially after
default sort direction is added.

Change-Id: Icd81aca5cd15e5ec34f081fe29fbad49dcccc45c

subject: Add extension discovery to core API.
messages:
[{'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-08-08 01:09:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So there are some elements in here i think may be contentions but i will give my reasonings first.

I am not advocating that extensions SHOULD put a version number into the discoverability. I think that a proper extension should treat itself as the root of a namespace and provide some discoverability on what versions of that are available. So for example, i can see a time where we would want http://identity/OS-TRUST/v2/trusts and figuring this out should fall to the extension code. What i think it provides is the ability for an extension that was not were not developed with this in mind a way of deconflicting rather than having OS-TRUST2 registered as a new extension. 

I have similar thoughts about extra, that if you want to query an extension for how it was configured you should probably ask the extension. However i don't see it as a big problem to provide the ability to GET /extensions/OS-EXT and have an 'enabled': ['feature1', 'feature5'] that is extension specific."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-08 02:04:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

This looks OK, but as an aside, is there a Registry for extensions somewhere (e.g. like an IANA web site). In other words, how does someone register a new OS extension, where is the list of existing registered extensions published, and how are names chosen/agreed to e.g. is it first come first served for extension names, or is there some other way of determining what "official" OS names should be.'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-08-15 01:12:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@David, not as such no. Essentially it will be first come first served for things that have an API spec in the identity-api repository. The current convention for extensions is 'OS-{NAME}' so prefixed with 'OS-' and a name in all caps. AFAIK this is not specified anywhere."}]

commit_message:
Add extension discovery to core API.

Add a mechanism to discover the extensions that are available on the
server and the entry point to using them.

Change-Id: I40d90085aa546e4eb78acd86e9e67b4c8d27c875

commit_message:
Package dib-run-parts

dib-run-parts is a symlink into the elements directory.

During packaging the symlink is preserved however
during installation dib-run-parts becomes a file containing
the contents of the symlink target.

Related-Bug: #1212482
Change-Id: I78c28a52689810a2ccfc9925a9ac8df017c44326

commit_message:
Assume we always have /etc/keystone/keystone.conf.

We're not running in semi-installed mode: os-apply-config always
creates keystone.conf for us, so we can be more direct in our logic.

Change-Id: I2965af54dd910ccb681d3ce1819be17a32046b33

commit_message:
Drop EC2 credential generation from init-keystone.

We don't use the EC2 credentials in any of our tooling, and they can
be created by an external API script should they be needed.

Change-Id: I1bf845cf2db339e127b8a12bab64890a46d9dd19

commit_message:
Add yum element.

The yum element provides for specific customizations
for yum based distros.  The included customization is
a yum cache mounted outside of the chroot so that yum
downloaded packages are reused on subsequent image builds.

Change-Id: I6833c9fdbc83cb09debec6a789082e105c917800

instructions.

[{'created': '2013-08-01 01:25:09.000000000', 'message': 'Move NameDispatch creation out of drivers

Certain drivers (eg, SSH and IPMI) must import conductor.task_manager to
get the require_exclusive_lock decorator. This, in turn, imports
conductor.resource_manager:NodeManager, which was instantiating
dispatch.NameDispatchExtensionManager on load. When this gets called
inside an entrypoint, it is creating a circular reference and erroring
out.

This match moves the creation of the NameDispatchExtensionManager to
conductor.manager:ConductorManager, and then assigns it to the
NodeManager class member driver_factory.

This is a very un-pythonic way of doing things and seems like
A Really Bad Idea. But it works.

This patch is just a demonstration of one way to fix this.

DO NOT MERGE.

Change-Id: I59c8705d1fbcc41b0a34ffb203ca907dedb15df5

commit_message:
Fix driver loading

Driver loading is broken due to a circular import.
This patch fixes it by moving the instantiation of stevedore's
NameDispatchExtensionManager out of parse time so that it isn't
re-invoked each time stevedore imports another driver module.

Fixes bug 1212030

Change-Id: I59c8705d1fbcc41b0a34ffb203ca907dedb15df5

commit_message:
fix: fetching nonexistent message/claims raises 503s

The proposed fix moves away from throwing an exception everytime a
malformed ID is encountered and instead returns None. This way,
partial bulk get and bulk deletes are possible.

Storage drivers affected:
- mongo
- sqlite

Changes/expected behavior:
- GET /v1/queues/exists/messages/malformed => 404
- GET /v1/queues/exists/messages?ids=malformed,malformed => 204
- DELETE /v1/queues/exists/messages?ids=malformed,malformed => 204
- GET /v1/queues/exists/claims/malformed => 404
- PATCH /v1/queues/exists/claims/malformed => 404
- DELETE /v1/queues/exists/claims/malformed => 204

In partcular, regarding bulk_get on messages, malformed IDs or
messages that are not found by ID are now ignored. bulk_delete also
works in this fashion now.

Regression tests are added to the unit test suite to reflect these
changes.

Change-Id: I4f14cd8b4cfd1dd190dccd8724c20f5fac99c629
Closes-Bug: #1203842

commit_message:
Stop checking periods in commit messages

This breaks various peoples fingers and there was no overwhelming
community support, nor historical evidence, for enforcing the proposed
rule in either direction.

Change-Id: Id2a5af9bb8a49af0a2f94b38a8e7d5ef1208e627

commit_message:
Fixes issue with command escaping on Windows

Fixes bug: #1210912

Special characters like <, > or ' need to be escaped on Windows when used
with "cmd /C <command>" as implemented in _run_shell_command

In order to avoid escaping issues, shell spawning has been replaced with
direct command execution. As a consequence, grep/egrep command pipes have
been replaced with Python regular expressions where appropriate.

Change-Id: Idd50fd24f300bce655f99d42cb96e37d29d4cb14

commit_message:
python3: Fix traceback while running tests

Fix:

TypeError: Unicode-objects must be encoded before hashing

while running tests. This is due to the fact in python3 hashlib.md5
works with bytes and we are passing unicode strings.

Change-Id: I27a57d6afb2412e11bc2802e4559d56c5b5592a9
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

Gate on Python 3.3

This makes OS-jenkins run our tests in Python 3.3 mode in addition to
Python 2.6 and Python 2.7.

Rationale: keep our Python 3 compatibility high

build every book only once

At the moment a wrong check makes it possible that affected books
are build several times. That's not useful and should be changed.

Change-Id: I27c016c6d4ef98fead53609013c46302fa8b67d2

Add wrap_name param to the iptables_manager class

Use this optional parameter instead
of binary_name to wrap the chain names.

Fixes: bug #1194049

The DHCP build process will pin the version

Without setting the version, we end up with a dnsmasq
binary that reports an UNKNOWN version which quantum
raises an exception on

Can somebody review/approve this change?'}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2013-08-14 08:24:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(5 inline comments)

-1 due to not supporting running of migrations 'offline' and a possible issue with PostgreSQL.

As for running DB schema migrations on SQLite effort...

You must know that SQLite has very limited support of ALTER statement, which makes it rather hard to run DB migrations (though it can be done with 'recreate a table' workaround, which is both ugly and error-prone).

So, I believe, the game is not worth the candle. SQLite is not used in production, so you don't really need to upgrade existing installations. For new installations and running of tests it's possible to generate DB schema based on models definitions."}, {'account_id': 6522, 'date': '2013-08-14 10:39:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I have no idea what you mean by running migrations offline, also what is the possible issue with PostresSQL? These changes do not alter any current migrations and only add support for SQLite. 

I am well aware of the limitations of SQLite and the problems incurred. Having SQLite supports greatly helps for testing purposes and development purposes where a full fledged database is not accessible.'}, {'account_id': 6522, 'date': '2013-08-14 11:02:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: No score

Disregard offline migrations and PostgreSQL comments. 

Still it is important to have sqlite support, and you cannot claim that sqlite isn't being used if it is not supported."}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2013-08-14 11:21:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

'offline' migrations feature is briefly described here: 
https://alembic.readthedocs.org/en/latest/tutorial.html#generating-sql-scripts-a-k-a-offline-mode

As for the issue with PostgreSQL: you can't use integer literals 0 and 1 in boolean context. Please see:
http://xsnippet.org/359595/raw/

But that's exactly what you are doing in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/40728/10/neutron/db/migration/alembic_migrations/versions/128e042a2b68_ext_gw_mode.py Line 56-57

I'm not against supporting migrations on SQLite, but I'd rather we first have flawless (no such data type errors on PostgreSQL) and feature-rich (offline migrations) support of production RDBMSs - MySQL and PostgreSQL."}, {'account_id': 6522, 'date': '2013-08-14 11:34:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 6522, 'date': '2013-08-14 11:36:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

commit_message:
Cleanup try/except/finally blocks in several tests

There are several tests that have large try/except blocks which catch
Exception and then log their own error message but don't include the
original exception message. Some of these also have finally blocks doing
cleanup which could be performed with a call to self.addCleanup in the
test itself. Since this patch removes the useless self.fail with a
custom message masking the original exception, I also refactored the
finally blocks to use addCleanup instead.

Fixes bug 1207893

Change-Id: I6e9532e5067bbc0458ed3dc3faac58151aa696a0

[{'created': '2013-08-13 20:31:31.000000000', 'message': "Adds Support for Managing the Token Driver Backend

Previously the keystone class did not manage the token driver.
High-Availability deployments of Keystone must use the SQL
driver so that all Keystone instances can access the same token
from a SQL database cluster.

The patch adds the token_driver parameter that is used to manage
the selection of the token driver backend in keystone.conf.
The parameter defaults to 'keystone.token.backends.kvs.Token' for
backwards compatibility and to use the KVS backend driver.

Change-Id: I4879052b7e44272c176814d048f916cb77d33581
"}]
commit_message:
Adds Support for Managing the Token Driver Backend

Previously the keystone class did not manage the token driver.
High-Availability deployments of Keystone must use the SQL
driver so that all Keystone instances can access the same token
from a SQL database cluster.

The patch adds the token_driver parameter that is used to manage
the selection of the token driver backend in keystone.conf.
The parameter defaults to 'keystone.token.backends.kvs.Token' for
backwards compatibility and to use the KVS backend driver.

Change-Id: I4879052b7e44272c176814d048f916cb77d33581

OK, the logic here is a little wonky.  I would argue that deleting the signing Dir is an indicator of something else wrong.  A better solution would be to restart Nova, as a secure temporary directory should not be recreated this way.

I think that this fix is treating the symptom, and not the cure.  If something external deletes the directory, it is messing with Nova, and that change needs to be dealt with.

It is quite possible that nova will still fail, even with this change, as the directory is not guaranteed to be one that the Nova user has permissions to create. 

If the signing dir was originally created with mkstemp, it should be recreated with that call, and not by regenerating the original directory.'}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-08-06 17:33:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

agree with the fix being wrong, but "deleting the signing Dir is an indicator of something else wrong" isn't true either ... i'd expect that purging /tmp should be a safe. auth_token should simply recreate the directory using it's normal process (it shouldn't be handled exceptionally). so, the fix should be more of a refactor than adding additional behavior'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2013-08-06 22:51:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(4 inline comments)

"}, {'account_id': 6731, 'date': '2013-08-07 16:17:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Rather than just adding another os.makedirs, which is just a workaround, you should fix the design issue: don't makedirs in the constructor of AuthProtocol, make it when you need to write to the dir.  Having two os.makedirs that do the same thing is confusing and code bloat."}, {'account_id': 6731, 'date': '2013-08-07 16:25:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: No score

> OK, the logic here is a little wonky. I would argue that deleting the signing Dir 
> is an indicator of something else wrong. A better solution would be to restart
> Nova, as a secure temporary directory should not be recreated this way.

@ayoung, As the bug report says, the signing dir defaults to a file in /tmp (well, whatever tempfile.mkdtemp returns).  It is valid to delete files in /tmp at anytime.  Doing valid system cleanup (pruning /tmp) shouldn't require a nova restart.

Perhaps it should default to putting it somewhere like /var, which doesn't get pruned."}, {'account_id': 6282, 'date': '2013-08-08 00:22:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-08 01:22:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Refactor verify signing dir logic

Add a function AuthProtocol::verify_signing_dir() in
keystoneclient/middleware/auth_token.py. It will be called both in init
stage and in fetching signing cert scenario.

Fixes bug 1201577

Change-Id: Ice0e8a93ba9d85c20de84cf8da3e9b0f2274b740

commit_message:
added new tag for testonly packages in lists

Also introduced a new parameter INSTALL_TESTONLY_PACKAGES
in the stackrc with False as default value. Setting it to
True stack.sh will install all packages tagged with the tag
testonly in the package lists.

fixes bug #1203680

Change-Id: I911a6601819a34262853bba0658f6751148bfbec

commit_message:
Unset OS_xx variable before generate configuration

When generate_sample.sh generate the configuration of the
keystone middleware part, it use OS_XXXXX environment
variable if this one is set instead of the default one.

This change unset this variables, before generate_sample.sh
inspect the code to always have the default value.

Change-Id: I4f41eece3d93633fcc07274f533adfa1887325fc

commit_message:
remove _action_change_password the attribute in V3 server API

There is no implementation of _action_change_password for the
attribute of ActionDeserializer in V3 server API. Get rid of it

fix bug 1209072

commit_message:
Oozie bug-fixing

* Oozie can be installed only in single instance
* Added oozie-default.xml to plugin configs
* Added unit-test for Oozie
* Defined which configs needed to push as defaults to oozie-site.xml
* Now user able to push configs for oozie-site.xml
* heap-size and log redirection will be in the next CR

blueprint edp-oozie-for-vanilla-plugin

Change-Id: I2e58bde39f573127352dcf20daa3d7bef19d4c22

Mongodb's driver uses Claim's creation time to estimate claims age
instead, it should use claim's update time. Since there's no update /
creation time in mongodb's claims, the patch estimates claims age by
doing:

    delta(expiration - ttl, now)

This change fixes the issue bellow and makes mongodb's claims compliant

commit_message:
Don't use claim creation time to calc claim's age

Mongodb's driver uses Claim's creation time to estimate claims age
instead, it should use claim's update time. Since there's no update /
creation time in mongodb's claims, the patch estimates claims age by
doing:

    delta(expiration - ttl, now)

This change fixes the issue bellow and makes mongodb's claims compliant
with Marconi's specs.

Change-Id: I72c968236ecd239e7b885b293238e2920807a57c
Closes-Bug: #1210662

commit_message:
Install gettext in base test setup

All ceilometer service/agent use gettextutils.install but
gettext method _ is even installed for test

This change, install gettext method _ in base test instead of
import it on each file only for test.

commit_message:
Fixes some unseen flake8 violations.

The failures aren't visible when run from
cinder.  Nova has different settings for
flake8.  This patch fixes the violations
that nova's flake8 tests.

fixes Bug #1211935

Change-Id: I80209130de23842a0a35cacb7d59f166e7dba89f

commit_message:
fix: rename _payload_uplimit into _paging_uplimit

Although "message_paging_uplimit" also limit the maximum number of
IDs can be supplied in a URI, which is not quite a "page" (in bulk
deletion), but we don't need the configuration to be too precise.

Change-Id: I0737146f1212c82db18de35e35206d3932a46628

commit_message:
Fix boot instance with config drive

Instances would fail to boot if config drive was requested.
The error in the log was like:

 ERROR nova.compute.manager
 ...
 '  File "/opt/stack/nova/nova/api/metadata/base.py", line 344,
 in _check_version\n    return versions.index(requested) >= versions.index(required)\n',
 "ValueError: '2012-08-10' is not in list\n"]

Change-Id: I49ef1dc0a02034cb6edc26b1b7eedd786a720942
Resolves-Bug: #1211978

commit_message:
Start refactoring dynamic UI.

1. When using $value for form field attribute, first try
cleaned_data. And only if it is absent, use raw data.

2. Move all service fields classes into separate module fields.py

3. Move some helpers to helpers.py and rename __common.py to forms.py.

Change-Id: Iba27cb2f9bc1c017443e0666aa274b5f88373045

'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-08-12 11:36:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Do not merge

This is a straight copy from another project (with a different licence). Fortunately, it is under the MIT licence, so that isn't a show-stopper, but we need to do this properly.

* Please put this class in a separate module and import it only if the import from SQLAlchemy fails (i.e. if we are running <0.8).
* Ensure that the new module contains all appropriate copyright information from SQLAlchemy.
* I don't know if there's some other procedure we're required to follow?"}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-08-12 11:40:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

The CLA states:

"Should You wish to submit work that is not Your original creation, You may submit it to the Project Manager separately from any Contribution, identifying the complete details of its source and of any license or other restriction (including, but not limited to, related patents, trademarks, and license agreements) of which you are personally aware, and conspicuously marking the work as "Submitted on behalf of a third-party: [named here]"."'}, {'account_id': 7162, 'date': '2013-08-13 03:01:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 7162, 'date': '2013-08-13 03:05:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I extract the MutableDict to a seperate mudule and import it only when we use sqlalchemy < 0.8, copied the license info from sqlalchemy's source code, and conspicuously marking the work as "Submitted on behalf of a third-party: sqlalchemy."

I am not familiar with this process, I don't really know if it is enough.'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-08-13 03:26:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi Lei, thanks for sticking with a very difficult issue.

The original file has this at the top:

# Copyright (C) 2005-2013 the SQLAlchemy authors and contributors <see AUTHORS file>
#

Of course, in true Copyright notice form, there is no AUTHORS file. So I think replicating that Copyright notice, and noting the version that was imported, is probably enough.

Also from Zane's quote, it seems our "Project manager" (which I believe means PTL?) should +2. shardy?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-13 03:42:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Doesn't seem to work

More info:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LegalIssuesFAQ#Incorporating_BSD.2FMIT_Licensed_Code

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/legal-discuss/2013-April/000002.html

commit_message:
Handle heat with SQLAlchemy >= 0.8

Lots of unit tests failed with the new SQLAlchemy(0.8.2)
which makes build failed, this patch will fix all the related
bug like no MutableType and changed module name in SQLAlchemy(0.8.2)

Fixes bug #1199435

Change-Id: I67d7588db088dd3dd88d44c32e78c6b8a4708bff

commit_message:
Add initial version of the REST api for the job origin component

This change adds stubs for the REST api methods for the job
origin component, including schemas for validation.  As of yet,
there is no actual creation of database objects for job origins.
Names/values in the JSON schemas have been made all lowercase.

Implements: blueprint edp-job-origin-component

Change-Id: I3158e414e3f51fadfe5ba98c534ee241c737a91d

commit_message:
Made Ambari RPM location configurable

The Ambari RPM location is now an ambari configuration property in
the blueprint.  This will support debug/issue resolution scenarios
as well as the export of this information.

Fixes:  bug #1208966

Change-Id: Ie0bfbd39d687c8c26d654b7fcfb369f764d48ef2

[{'created': '2013-08-14 10:09:19.000000000', 'message': "Implement dynamic UI for all current service creation forms.

1. Show only selected service description in Create Service step0
form.

2. Move template names and params postprocessing into service forms.

3. Move all forms post-processing (before passing to api) into
declarative specs. All post-processing is actually performed in
extract_attributes form functions according to attributeNames
attr. for each field in each form.

4. Support generation of multiple forms (steps) from one service
definition.

5. Dynamic forms UI use services yaml-description.

6. Use predefined field types instead of eval-ing python object
names. Also use camelCased names instead of pythonic_ones.

7. Localize string values for predefined keys and do not use string
prefix.

8. Add verify password fields automatically for each password field.

9. Use attributeNames for each field description instead. Value of
attributeNames can be:
* list - field value will propagated to multiple attributes;
* omitted - field value will be propagated to attribute with same
  name;
* false - field value won't be propagated to any attribute;
* string - field value will be propagated to attribute whose name is
 specified by the string, with one note: `attributeNames: domain.x'
 for field `A' will produce attribute value `domain: {x: A.value}'

10. Remove django template from service description. Use per-field
descriptions. If the field in service's description has attribute
`description', it is automatically inserted into appropriate form
description. If `descriptionTitle' attribute is present, it becomes
the title of field description, else `label' attribute is used.

11. Also in addition to an existing regexp literal (quoted string) add
new one: quoted string with slashes: '/some-regexp/flags'. Flags is
split into list of 1-letter strings <flag>, each of them is uppercased
to <FLAG> and sent to re.compile as getattr(re, <FLAG>).

Change-Id: I76c25cbbd682823cbef2693b51ccd69ffe83b6d4
"}]
commit_message:
Implement dynamic UI for all current service creation forms.

1. Show only selected service description in Create Service step0
form.

2. Move template names and params postprocessing into service forms.

3. Move all forms post-processing (before passing to api) into
declarative specs. All post-processing is actually performed in
extract_attributes form functions according to attributeNames
attr. for each field in each form.

4. Support generation of multiple forms (steps) from one service
definition.

5. Dynamic forms UI use services yaml-description.

6. Use predefined field types instead of eval-ing python object
names. Also use camelCased names instead of pythonic_ones.

7. Localize string values for predefined keys and do not use string
prefix.

8. Add verify password fields automatically for each password field.

9. Use attributeNames for each field description instead. Value of
attributeNames can be:
* list - field value will propagated to multiple attributes;
* omitted - field value will be propagated to attribute with same
  name;
* false - field value won't be propagated to any attribute;
* string - field value will be propagated to attribute whose name is
 specified by the string, with one note: `attributeNames: domain.x'
 for field `A' will produce attribute value `domain: {x: A.value}'

10. Remove django template from service description. Use per-field
descriptions. If the field in service's description has attribute
`description', it is automatically inserted into appropriate form
description. If `descriptionTitle' attribute is present, it becomes
the title of field description, else `label' attribute is used.

11. Also in addition to an existing regexp literal (quoted string) add
new one: quoted string with slashes: '/some-regexp/flags'. Flags is
split into list of 1-letter strings <flag>, each of them is uppercased
to <FLAG> and sent to re.compile as getattr(re, <FLAG>).

Change-Id: I76c25cbbd682823cbef2693b51ccd69ffe83b6d4

commit_message:
Add more API documentation for record types

Add examples to the REST API documentation section for each of
the record types supported. Currently, there are only examples
for types 'A' and 'MX'.

Change-Id: Iba9a8e4b88312b6266b46fb3e353076dd03cab8f
Fixes: bug #1204578

[{'created': '2013-08-13 14:12:47.000000000', 'message': "Implement dynamic UI for all current service creation forms.

1. Show only selected service description in Create Service step0
form.

2. Move template names and params postprocessing into service forms.

3. Move all forms post-processing (before passing to api) into
declarative specs. All post-processing is actually performed in
extract_attributes form functions according to attributeNames
attr. for each field in each form.

4. Support generation of multiple forms (steps) from one service
definition.

5. Dynamic forms UI use services yaml-description.

6. Use predefined field types instead of eval-ing python object
names. Also use camelCased names instead of pythonic_ones.

7. Localize string values for predefined keys and do not use string
prefix.

8. Add verify password fields automatically for each password field.

9. Use attributeNames for each field description instead. Value of
attributeNames can be:
* list - field value will propagated to multiple attributes;
* omitted - field value will be propagated to attribute with same
  name;
* false - field value won't be propagated to any attribute;
* string - field value will be propagated to attribute whose name is
 specified by the string, with one note: `attributeNames: domain.x'
 for field `A' will produce attribute value `domain: {x: A.value}'

10. Remove django template from service description. Use per-field
descriptions. If the field in service's description has attribute
`description', it is automatically inserted into appropriate form
description. If `descriptionTitle' attribute is present, it becomes
the title of field description, else `label' attribute is used.

11. Also in addition to an existing regexp literal (quoted string) add
new one: quoted string with slashes: '/some-regexp/flags'. Flags is
split into list of 1-letter strings <flag>, each of them is uppercased
to <FLAG> and sent to re.compile as getattr(re, <FLAG>).

Change-Id: I76c25cbbd682823cbef2693b51ccd69ffe83b6d4

commit_message:
Implement dynamic UI for all current service creation forms.

1. Show only selected service description in Create Service step0
form.

2. Move template names and params postprocessing into service forms.

3. Move all forms post-processing (before passing to api) into
declarative specs. All post-processing is actually performed in
extract_attributes form functions according to attributeNames
attr. for each field in each form.

4. Support generation of multiple forms (steps) from one service
definition.

5. Dynamic forms UI use services yaml-description.

6. Use predefined field types instead of eval-ing python object
names. Also use camelCased names instead of pythonic_ones.

7. Localize string values for predefined keys and do not use string
prefix.

8. Add verify password fields automatically for each password field.

9. Use attributeNames for each field description instead. Value of
attributeNames can be:
* list - field value will propagated to multiple attributes;
* omitted - field value will be propagated to attribute with same
  name;
* false - field value won't be propagated to any attribute;
* string - field value will be propagated to attribute whose name is
 specified by the string, with one note: `attributeNames: domain.x'
 for field `A' will produce attribute value `domain: {x: A.value}'

10. Remove django template from service description. Use per-field
descriptions. If the field in service's description has attribute
`description', it is automatically inserted into appropriate form
description. If `descriptionTitle' attribute is present, it becomes
the title of field description, else `label' attribute is used.

11. Also in addition to an existing regexp literal (quoted string) add
new one: quoted string with slashes: '/some-regexp/flags'. Flags is
split into list of 1-letter strings <flag>, each of them is uppercased
to <FLAG> and sent to re.compile as getattr(re, <FLAG>).

Change-Id: I76c25cbbd682823cbef2693b51ccd69ffe83b6d4

commit_message:
Add a get_data function to Service Catalog

Service catalog takes as a parameter the entire token. This makes it
difficult to extract only the service catalog component without querying
the catalog version, which should be unnecessary.

Change-Id: I3ad428fcb3279e8aa607f67f58265a085ae63440

commit_message:
Extract basic request call

Create a function out of the standard request call that handles common
headers like user agent and logging.
This makes future changes easier to digest.

Change-Id: Ia25f997df64efdce27c8fb815e544922940145c3

commit_message:
Switch to Oslo-Incubator's EnvFilter rootwrap

Nova-Network used to have its own class for DnsMasq rootwrap
filtering. This was generalized into a new EnvFilter rootwrap
filter that can specify both commands and environments to pass.

Update to openstack.common.rootwrap to git a117358 of
oslo-incubator's rootwrap. This includes the following commits
merged from oslo:

    3b16d31 Remove DnsmasqFilter and DeprecatedDnsmasqFilter
    f9d1a59 Handle empty arglists in Filters
    233baa2 Handle empty PATH environment variable
    3e74c00 Add IpFilter, IPNetnsExecFilter and EnvFilter
    8b95b1e Handle relative path arguments in Killfilter
    7119e29 Enable hacking H404 test.
    ea78eec Update KillFilter to stop at '\0' for readlink() function.

Related to: blueprint quantum-common-rootwrap

Change-Id: I125e5724259850dc4768fb236cbfa5df199008c0

commit_message:
Adds hypervisor statistics to admin dashboard

Uses the existing d3 visualizations along with the hypervisor
stats API in Nova to display some useful at-a-glance information
about the utilization of your cloud.

Implements blueprint hypervisor-info

commit_message:
Allow a list of Maps on the json property

This will allow the following to be passed into a Map property/parameter
[{Name: the_key, Value: the_val},
 {Name: a_key, Value: a_val}]

This is typical in AWS::Cloudwatch::Alarm Dimensions

Change-Id: I1c1f349665819a6f2395875744e5b636c2b5bf7f

'}, {'account_id': 7135, 'date': '2013-08-09 15:29:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Just a quick question. The resolve function isn't added to static or runtime resolve. I wonder how is it used, is it supposed to be referenced in upcoming patches?"}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-08-12 11:06:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I have mixed feelings about this, it *sounds* like a generic function, but when you look at the AWS specs you find there are a whole lot of defined types, many of which can appear in lists:

http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-product-property-reference.html

but only one I can find that uses "Name" and "Value" as keys:

http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-properties-cw-dimension.html

for example, EC2 Tags use "Key" and "Value":

http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-properties-ec2-tags.html

so this is really a function for a single resource type, which sucks :(

Given this, and given that most of the types listed above have more than just a single key/value anyway, I think it would be better to follow AWS's lead and define all such properties as a list with a fixed schema for its items, rather than a dictionary with a free-form schema.

However, that still poses the problem of how to translate those types for provider templates, since we won't want OpenStack resources to use the same names as AWS. I don't have a good answer for this that isn't getting close to effectively implementing Fn::ForEach, which folks have said in the past they don't want (maybe we need to revisit though?).'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-08-14 07:48:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned

better solution in another patch'}]

commit_message:
Enable H201: do not write "except:"

Fixes all occurrences of this. We have a custom exception handler
in Horizon anyway that only catches ClientException in most of these
cases, but this commit lets us gate on the other cases.

Change-Id: Iea3dc13817f3e5b775b2024424bf3a906da5584b
Closes-Bug: #1211657

Skeletal alarm history API

A 'history' custom action is provided on the individual
alarm controller, always empty initially.

Precursor to support for bp alarm-audit-api

commit_message:
Reorg alarms controller to facilitate history API

Use controller/sub-controller pattern for the alarms collection and
individual alarms respectively (as we do for meters).

This will facilitate the addition of a 'history' custom action on
individual alarms.

Precursor to support for bp alarm-audit-api

Change-Id: I8e43cebdc82f05b2cc427c7a27114101836dbf5f

commit_message:
Move 'tests' directory into 'keystone' package

Similar to a range of other components (e.g. glance,nova,...) and recent
reviews by Monty.

Running individual tests can be done like this:

./run_tests.sh keystone.tests.test_drivers

Change-Id: I2482a48322150e5eb09b703326a94d8283f1c75b

[{'created': '2013-08-13 13:21:03.000000000', 'message': 'Stub ResourceWithProps instead of GenericResource

Stubbing methods in a superclass is an all-or-nothing affair: once a stub
in the subclass is unset, the subclass will no longer inherit changes in
the superclass (i.e. if you then stub out the same method in the
superclass, the subclass will be unaffected).

Previously, we always set the stubs in the superclass (for historical
reasons, to avoid making this change). This would lead to tests that want
to differentiate between types (by stubbing in the derived class)
interfering with the operation of other tests. This patch changes to always
setting the stubs in the derived class.

Change-Id: I2c8dbd22826da14611a6a3f55321f0016446580a
'}]
commit_message:
Stub ResourceWithProps instead of GenericResource

Stubbing methods in a superclass is an all-or-nothing affair: once a stub
in the subclass is unset, the subclass will no longer inherit changes in
the superclass (i.e. if you then stub out the same method in the
superclass, the subclass will be unaffected).

Previously, we always set the stubs in the superclass (for historical
reasons, to avoid making this change). This would lead to tests that want
to differentiate between types (by stubbing in the derived class)
interfering with the operation of other tests. This patch changes to always
setting the stubs in the derived class.

Change-Id: I2c8dbd22826da14611a6a3f55321f0016446580a

commit_message:
Enable conversion for composite attribute items

Bug 1207881

Enable 'dict validators' to convert composite attributes' items
using a 'convert_to' specification in a way similar to first-level
API attributes.
This is needed in order to ensure boolean sub-attributes are
properly handled.

Change-Id: I7f466befaa88112cf7e9b77d854ac292b2af638f

Nachi,

> Patch Set 25:
>
> I'm not sure how this code handling for failure for fw deletion. What's if server side model is deleted during l3-agent dies? FW rules looks still remaining

If L3 Agent is down and the firewall is deleted, the firewall will be in PENDING_DELETE state. When L3 agent is restarted, it will synch with the plugin and the firewall will get deleted (this was tested and verified)."}, {'account_id': 7752, 'date': '2013-07-16 10:38:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27:

Nachi> May be, I'm missing something, but FW get error state

Nachi, the devstack changes may not be in yet. When you start L3 agent, please pass "-config-file=/etc/neutron/fwaas_driver.ini" to the agent.

The sample fwaas_driver.ini file is at neutron/etc/ directory.

Please uncomment the 'driver' line from the INI file.

If you do not do this, the agent uses Noop firewall which sets the status as ERROR.'}, {'account_id': 6659, 'date': '2013-07-16 12:16:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27: (1 inline comment)

Looks pretty good to me. Just a small refinement to the duplication removal...'}, {'account_id': 2031, 'date': '2013-07-16 13:40:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27:

OK Thanks! Rajesh

What's if fw deletion failure?
Is that not fixed until l3-agent restart?"}, {'account_id': 7752, 'date': '2013-07-16 17:53:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27:

Nachi>> What's if fw deletion failure? Is that not fixed until l3-agent restart?

If the failure is permanent (say someone deleted namespace manually), then there is not much we can do. Retrying this  operation will probably create mode damage than good. IMO, logging failure and waiting on manual intervention (restarting L3 agent or following other troubleshooting steps) is desirable. We should probably update the troubleshooting section of the document to cover this.

If we know for sure that the failure is temporary (say due to lack of resource), I would agree that we should have some build in mechanism to retry on failure. At this point, the failures are most likely to be permanent."}, {'account_id': 2031, 'date': '2013-07-16 17:56:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27:

OK so how about rabbitmq down, and we lose fw delete message?'}, {'account_id': 2031, 'date': '2013-07-16 18:17:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27:

Nachi>> OK so how about rabbitmq down, and we lose fw delete message?

Good point. We discussed (Sumit[Plugin] and Sridar[Agent]) and decided to do a periodic sync between Agent and Plugin. This change will be in the Agent code and no changes are needed on the driver side.

Please note that driver code is idempotent. Applying same rules multiple times due to some corner case in periodic synch should not cause any problem (this will really be rare case as additional checks are done in agent to avoid unnecessary application of rules).'}, {'account_id': 2031, 'date': '2013-07-17 03:26:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28:

Thanks! I got it'}, {'account_id': 7752, 'date': '2013-07-17 03:27:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28:

Your INI file is in old format. The current INI file looks like

root@ubuntu:/opt/stack/neutron# cat /etc/neutron/fwaas_driver.ini
[fwaas]
driver = neutron.services.firewall.drivers.linux.iptables_fwaas.IptablesFwaasDriver

Please update and try again. Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 2031, 'date': '2013-07-17 03:28:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28:

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'message': 'Firewall as a Service (FWaaS) Iptables Driver

blueprint quantum-fwaas-iptables-driver

This is IPTables Driver for "Firewall As A
Service" feature.

This implements
- Fwaas rules are mapped to IPTables

commit_message:
Firewall as a Service (FWaaS) Iptables Driver

blueprint quantum-fwaas-iptables-driver

This is IPTables Driver for "Firewall As A
Service" feature.

This implements
- Fwaas rules are mapped to IPTables
- The rules are installed in the network
  namespace of quantum-routers

Change-Id: I157182f2c86fbcf8c141b9ad3cfc71168153ebf8

commit_message:
Added glance_request_timeout config option.

The glanceclient supports a timeout for http/https
connections but this is not configurable in cinder.
This patch adds a glance_request_timeout
option to cinder.conf. If unset, None is applied thus
allowing glanceclient to use its default value (600).

Change-Id: Ic689ecb5d5ee8257964b341b5a7980d5733343dc
Fixes: bug #1206992
Co-authored-by:  Takahiro Shida <shida@intellilink.co.jp>

[{'created': '2013-08-12 22:36:06.000000000', 'message': 'Derive keystone_ec2_uri from auth_uri

ec2token auth_uri must be correctly configured for heat to work.
The /ec2tokens path is not an endpoint in its own right, it is
part of the keystone v2.0 API. The keystone_ec2_uri configuration
parameter was only used for ec2 style credentials validation in
the ec2token middleware.  It might have also propagated all the
way into the user_creds table to be stored for each stack were it
not for this chain of failures (removed in this commit):

commit_message:
Derive keystone_ec2_uri from auth_uri

ec2token auth_uri must be correctly configured for heat to work.
The /ec2tokens path is not an endpoint in its own right, it is
part of the keystone v2.0 API. The keystone_ec2_uri configuration
parameter was only used for ec2 style credentials validation in
the ec2token middleware.  It might have also propagated all the
way into the user_creds table to be stored for each stack were it
not for this chain of failures (removed in this commit):
- X-Auth-EC2_URL header is set in ec2token, but header X-Auth-EC2-Url
  is read by RequestContext
- RequestContext stores the ec2 uri in aws_auth_uri, but UserCreds
  expects aws_auth_url

Change-Id: I9908e17bed33fdc64d058a6d6db7b29f9c8d53d6

commit_message:
Correct the sorting arrows in tables

Update the file "horizon.less".
According to the tablesorter on github, the direction of the arrow images are totally opposite.
However the images are referenced by other css styles.
So the best practice is updating the css styles instead of updating the name of image.

Change-Id: Ib5ffbcb907956e2621e5d9d23790de5d35c7d0cc
Fixes: bug #1189307

[{'created': '2013-08-02 05:02:38.000000000', 'message': "Use a dummy rpm for Fedora

On Fedora/RHEL python is setup with paths such that pip will install
into /usr rather than /usr/local (see sysconfig.get_paths()).  This
means rpm-packaged and pip-installed packages can't co-exist.

Since we want a later setuptools and pip installed, there is a
chicken-and-egg egg problem: we can't remove the python-setuptools rpm
because it flows through as a dependency to other packages we
need/want.  We can't pip install a later verison, because that will
imperfectly overwrite the packaged files and makes a mess of combined
versions that fails.

The solution presented here is to create a dummy rpm which gets
installed and provides python-setuptools, python-pip and some other
packages that we wish to install via pip, but are also requirements
for other rpm-packages we want (crypto and lxml currently).  The dummy
rpm ensures the dependencies are met and kicks out the existing
packages if installed (via rpm, so no trace is left).  We use
install_pip.sh written by Dean Troyer in [1] to install upstream pip
directly after that.

As a follow-on, we should probably remove all python-* rpm packages
from the Fedora install and let pip do the work.  The only issue is if
other rpm-packages we wish to use bring in python-* packages ... in
that case we probably need the dummy-package work-around for them.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/39827/

Change-Id: I3ec4ac01c2ec1fb1ce9844f12611d1f86d631991

commit_message:
Use a dummy rpm for Fedora

On Fedora/RHEL python is setup with paths such that pip will install
into /usr rather than /usr/local (see sysconfig.get_paths()).  This
means rpm-packaged and pip-installed packages can't co-exist.

Since we want a later setuptools and pip installed, there is a
chicken-and-egg egg problem: we can't remove the python-setuptools rpm
because it flows through as a dependency to other packages we
need/want.  We can't pip install a later verison, because that will
imperfectly overwrite the packaged files and makes a mess of combined
versions that fails.

The solution presented here is to create a dummy rpm which gets
installed and provides python-setuptools, python-pip and some other
packages that we wish to install via pip, but are also requirements
for other rpm-packages we want (crypto and lxml currently).  The dummy
rpm ensures the dependencies are met and kicks out the existing
packages if installed (via rpm, so no trace is left).  We use
install_pip.sh written by Dean Troyer in [1] to install upstream pip
directly after that.

As a follow-on, we should probably remove all python-* rpm packages
from the Fedora install and let pip do the work.  The only issue is if
other rpm-packages we wish to use bring in python-* packages ... in
that case we probably need the dummy-package work-around for them.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/39827/

Change-Id: I3ec4ac01c2ec1fb1ce9844f12611d1f86d631991

commit_message:
nova-api should check UTF8 char in parameters

Enter the instance name when you create a new instance. If you enter the instance name in particular unicode,
an error will occur. This error clear a list of all the instances in the dashboard.

Fixes : bug #940430

Change-Id: Ib298f9b8ed356a6e243fbfe0b16bcaaa3ceb88b7

commit_message:
Rule based access control improvements - Part 1

This change implements one of several proposed improvements
to the current rule based access control in Nova.  This change
removes the require_admin_context decorator in places where it
overrides the policy check rule defined in policy.json.  With this
change, a rule/role can b defined in policy.json to control access
to various apis without requiring the admin role.

Change-Id: I8221f82974a1bfd0fcab3548e754f5ff12a3ca15
Implements: blueprint rbac-improvements

commit_message:
Adding the -online option to the 3PAR clone

The 3PAR drivers had to wait while the clone was being performed
and this would take a considerable amount of time for large volumes.
This patch takes advantage of the 3PAR backend by using the -online
option in the command that we were calling to perform the copy. This
allows us to remove the sleep in the driver. Using the -online
option forced us to change some of the delete_volume code because
the 3PAR backend will not allow a volume that was copied to be added
to a virtual volume set.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I47d72063c858e2eee10756be4f74febdd1603179
Fixes: bug 1208586

commit_message:
Do not use -y for package install

As a followup to a patch for basic-install (see
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/30263/), here's an update
for the rest of the manual to remove -y as option for package
installations.

See also
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-docs/2013-May/001787.html

Change-Id: I3d3bcfac4d3ae41933b587f026e1f1c75f02ea08

commit_message:
tox.ini: Change sitepackages to False

To avoid issues with tox, we should use packages installed in the venv
instead of one from local system.

Fix bug #1206947

Change-Id: I8fb2a7c36c92882dc0427706ac7b470a3f3fcf42

commit_message: Interprete scoped key as nested tags Current codes in xml_util.py does not support REST xml so well when one tagname contains delimiter, it fails to be interpreted. So this patch is to interprete one tagname like "1" as a nested tag like "1". Fix bug:1205983 Change-Id: Ia3e1f4d6b6a739898b51bf052a784fa36ab7695e

commit_message:
Not to eat Metadata parsing error

Exception raised while resolving metadata is treated as database
exception and eaten.

A few testing errors are revealed after metadata parsing error is
propagated to callers.

Fixes bug #1207193

Change-Id: I3b5cc5fed3896b7fe59533c7d09f0226e5cf5ad9

commit_message:
Fixes volume clone from volume

Cloning a volume from another volume appeared
to have been broken by new create_volume
taskflow. Clone from snapshot was not affected.

Also added a unit test this scenario.

Change-Id: I4f174e1616f6944cce64f8d522fa42a9f00f55eb
Fixes: bug #1211709

commit_message:
Revert "Add missing _ imports to allow doc generation"

This change reverts commit 0453785f3f7b2a578b433cb0544394aac9bcfb95 and
fixes a bug where the _() was not being recognized when building the
documentation while preserving the delayed translation of error
messages.

Closes-Bug: #1211507
Related-Bug: #1209413

Change-Id: I5d52941e1f08ec656f7279efb6cdf496d81861da

[{'created': '2013-08-09 13:10:16.000000000', 'message': 'Ignore purge_props for v2 Glance api and fix upload

The V2 Glance API image schema does not contain
purge_props. While this may be a bug in Glance,
we will ignore this property in cinder when
glance_api_version=2. This will not change behaviour
since Glance defaults this property to True, Cinder
never sets it to False and the v2 client appears to
ignore it anyway.

Also fixed image upload which is a seperate client
call to update in v2 (v1 update does both).

Change-Id: I0ba1d7d920984cface57795ace160ec300ff75e2
Fixes: bug #1210467
'}]
commit_message:
Ignore purge_props for v2 Glance api and fix upload

The V2 Glance API image schema does not contain
purge_props. While this may be a bug in Glance,
we will ignore this property in cinder when
glance_api_version=2. This will not change behaviour
since Glance defaults this property to True, Cinder
never sets it to False and the v2 client appears to
ignore it anyway.

Also fixed image upload which is a seperate client
call to update in v2 (v1 update does both).

Change-Id: I0ba1d7d920984cface57795ace160ec300ff75e2
Fixes: bug #1210467

commit_message:
Add support for API message localization

Add support for doing language resolution for a request, based on the
Accept-Language HTTP header.

Using the lazy gettext functionality from oslo gettextutils, it is now
possible to use the resolved language to translate an exception message
to the user requested language and return that translation from the API.

Partially implements bp user-locale-api

Change-Id: Ib2c8360372996d53b50542df54a52d92b07295ca

Well, I think it would be better if we raise an exception based on OpenStackException in every places where an internal exception should be raised. Wrapping webob.exc in another exception makes thing a little complicate, IMHO. Let me give an example here, 

heat.api.openstack.v1.stack:L322:

        if 'Error' in result:
            raise exc.HTTPBadRequest(result['Error'])

should be replaced with

        if 'Error' in result:
            raise exc.StackValidationFailed(result['Error'])

Basically, I think it is not a good idea to raise webob exceptions directly since 

1) it doesn't represent the real error; and
2) webob swallows all webob.exc so that no middleware can catch it."}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-08-07 17:27:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Jianing YANG, 

I think being able to raise webob exceptions on the REST API components should not be forbidden. That is the right level of abstraction for those exceptions to be raised, just like the specific heat exceptions are at the right level where they are right now, since they are raised in the heat-engine.

I don't see anything wrong with each component using its own exception abstraction level, particularly when those exceptions are well known like in the case of the webob HTTP.excs. Not to say that reusing the heat exceptions from a level below at any level would be wrong, but I think creating a unique exception for each possible generic HTTP response error can lead to exception sprawl. 

Not only that, but looking at this and other REST APIs (e.g. nova, cinder, neutron, glance) it appears that the decision has already been made to enable the use of webob.excs in the REST API modules. 

Now, I don't know whether this should be a topic of discussion for this patch, since it is simply addressing the bug as described in that basically currently error responses are inconsistently sent back to the consumer based on the exception type. I think unifying exceptions across levels in the heat stack would be a different work item and maybe one that would need broader discussion.

Thank you."}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-08-07 17:28:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Ensure all REST API error responses are consistent

Heat exceptions are serialized into JSON/XML responses by the fault app,
which is at the end of the WSGI pipeline. Some REST API errors however
are raised as HTTPExceptions, which are treated by WSGI as responses
ready to be sent back to the user, and they can't reach the fault app.

This patch set disguises HTTPExceptions raised by the wsgi.Resource so
they can reach the app that will serialize them just like all other
errors.

Fixes bug 1208620

Change-Id: Id98dbc1e3b208401be8f0119a6d72d4561a2221a

commit_message:
Capture our heuristics for configuration.

Right now it's only hinted at in incubator + a single email. Lets have
a place to point folk at to read about it. Alternatively we could put
it in incubator, but I think the image-elements repository is shaping
up to be the prime repository of code for us.

Change-Id: Ief5a33887239d313a76dfca5cd78c6f9263873bf

commit_message:
Use correct actions for StackResource

To perform actions on a stack, we should use the action constants defined
in the Stack, not in another object (and especially not in a Resource).

Change-Id: I3044f6286fc2690c121a3446f42a6896b3ed3271

commit_message:
Use o-r-c instead of first-boot.d for iptables.

This is the only use of first-boot.d, which is somewhat problematic for
a number of reasons. Using o-r-c the script can be made semi-idempotent
and then we can consider eliminating first-boot.d from
diskimage-builder.

Change-Id: I6e675d4fddda44af388eb5eaea7b3a9697092948

commit_message:
Sync notifier module from Oslo

Pull in the common notifier from Oslo-incubator into Keystone. This only
introduces the notifier module and it's dependencies. This change is
standalone and doesn't contain any code to implementation notifications,
just the initial sync.

blueprint notifications

Change-Id: If62d6012a92e944f3196dd20e6cdd3236e7ecae2

commit_message:
python3: Add basic compatibility support

Use six.iteritems to replace dictionary.iteritems() on python2 or
dictionary.items() on python3.

Change-Id: I623009200f3a90985a2c0178673df7d54b36a686
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
Drop quantum dhcp lease update bin

In d9832282cf656b162c51afdefb830dacab72defe we dropped
the DHCP lease logic from neutron... including
the neutron-dhcp-agent-dnsmasq-lease-update.

Both the neutron and quantum bins were removed from setup.cfg
so we should also drop the quantum-dhcp-agent-dnsmasq-lease-update
as well.

Change-Id: I568845dc28aa4dc9012435de2f0689aafa00a43c

commit_message:
dkms is unavailable on RHEL and derivatives

The dynamic kernel module system is not available on RHEL, CentOS,
Scientific Linux, or SUSE.  Make it part of the distro post-install
rather then base post-install.

Change-Id: Ic2c345bf9f0738dadae611194e263d3a5d424a3e

As things have been factored out, boot-stack no longer implies
nova-compute on the same host. This specifically addresses the case
where we build the overcloud-control image and it fails to restart
nova-compute during post-configure because nova-compute defaults to
libvirt, but libvirt is only installed by the nova-kvm element.

Change-Id: I3cba8a48c64d3919898d4ea47a6cd7808327cd9c
'}]
commit_message:
Remove nova-compute from boot-stack dependencies.

As things have been factored out, boot-stack no longer implies
nova-compute on the same host. This specifically addresses the case
where we build the overcloud-control image and it fails to restart
nova-compute during post-configure because nova-compute defaults to
libvirt, but libvirt is only installed by the nova-kvm element.

Change-Id: I3cba8a48c64d3919898d4ea47a6cd7808327cd9c

allow subclasses to modify the parents model hooks

fixes bug 1210387

This change modifies the model hook processing to call the method on the
instance if a hook is registered as a string.  If the hook is a
callable, then callable is called with the hook arguments.

Change-Id: Id14ae89f3f12a500920d248226e0ecba8e35e74c

commit_message:
Refactor configuring of floating ips on a router.

This approach to configuring floating ips is stateless and idempotent.
This allows it to handle corner cases, such as reusing a floating ip
address with a different floating ip id in a way that is easier to
understand.

The concept is to wipe the floating ips clean and rebuild them each
time with the following optimizations.  To avoid bad performance in
manipulating iptables, it is called in the context of a call to
defer_apply_on.  To avoid a disruption in network flow a set
difference is use to determine the set of addresses that no longer
belong on the inteface rather than removing them all blindly.

Change-Id: I0cfb58d487b1925e0a0db2a701c5ea3c56a0b2b5
Fixes: Bug #1209011

Wordpress NoKey template for F19

Example F19 WordPress NoKey template

Note mariadb changed and the upstream images do not ship with
firewalld enabled, but instead all incoming connections are blocked.

commit_message:
Initial implementation of unified-logging

This is the base implementation of a unified logging solution for
Keystone from Oslo-incubator. More work is still needed to refactor the
rest of Keystone such that it is completely dependent on the
implementation from Oslo and not the older keystone/common/logging.py
implementation, this is also noted in keystone/common/config.py.

blueprint unified-logging-in-keystone

Change-Id: I711cbac8edd887c52114fb13327e37124ea86737

BTW, we want to support search instances by 'soft-delete' instances. Maybe we should add a test to make sure input is 'soft-delete' and output is vm_states.SOFT_DELETED"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-07-25 14:12:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

Tiantian, the problem with the tests is that the mapping is common across all versions of the API, and right now the mapping for SOFT_DELETED is 'DELETED', so the only way to get that mapped to 'SOFT_DELETED' in the tests would be to (1) change the mapping in common.py (which was shot down in the initial patch set) or (2) completely duplicate the mapping and isolate it for the v3 API only, which I felt would be pretty ugly.  I sought some opinions on that via the mailing list but no one really had anything to say about it, so I decided to just leave it as-is."}, {'account_id': 1678, 'date': '2013-07-26 03:08:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Matt, I know it's a hard work. But without distinguish soft-deleted and deleted. The deferred deleting is very hard to use.

To this patch, we want to get instance which is 'soft-deleted', but the response instances status is 'DELETED', right?

Since origin api can't be modified, How about modify the STATE_MAP in V3 API. What I means is mapping vm_states.SOFT_DELETED to 'SOFT_DELETED'. 

In details, how about adding a new parameter "state_map" into common.status_from_state() and common.vm_state_from_status(). If "state_map" is specified, using it. Otherwise using the old one. The main logic of the two method don't need to change, and looks tiny. Make sense?'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-07-26 13:16:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Tiantian, I don't think that's a bad idea, but the other problem, and this is part of the reason I didn't think I could easily override the status mapping, was the view is using the common state map and that sits outside the v3 API plugin code:

https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/api/openstack/compute/views/servers.py#L148

So even if you do override the state mapping in the v3 API code, the view will still be returning the original common state mapping with 'DELETED' for SOFT_DELETED, so it doesn't really buy you anything.  And I don't think the view should probably be trying to use a v3-specific state mapping, at least I'm not aware of it doing anything like that already."}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2013-07-26 13:48:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm not completely up to speed with delete vs soft-delete discussion, but there are cases where we have had to make V3 specific views. See views/images.py as an example.

Mauro has a changeset going through at the moment which is modifying the servers view for v3 (though where it lives is about to change). So you might want to chat to him about it."}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2013-08-09 19:08:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-08-11 11:05:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Do not merge

This patch only allows SOFT_DELETED as a filter as input.  As far as I can tell, SOFT_DELETED is never exposed via the API.  I don't think it makes sense to allow it as input unless there is a more sweeping change to expose this concept via the API.  If we did *that* (expose the concept of a soft delete), I would also expect the ability to undo a delete that is pending ... basically I think it should be nothing, or much more change than this (I think I just prefer nothing personally)."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-08-11 14:32:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I'm OK with that - should I mark the bug as "Won't Fix" then?'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-08-13 22:03:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Abandoned

I'll post the -2 comment in the bug report and remove myself as the assignee."}]

commit_message:
Fix V3 OS API soft-delete mapping and error on invalid status filter

This patch makes a distinction between DELETED and SOFT_DELETED vm_state
values in the V3 OS API so a user can filter a server list using
SOFT_DELETED.

This patch also changes the V3 OS API server list behavior in that if
an invalid status filter value is passed, a BadRequest is raised so the
user knows their filter is wrong. Previously the API would just return
an empty list which is confusing from a usability perspective.

Fixes bug 1196255

Change-Id: I4ecd0e30c3fffba6b623c0023044dc0b03299065

is installing files to BUILDROOT/.pyenv/... instead of using paths

Change-Id: I1d7deca736cfa1bb0c8ea842113ba4daa33c41fd
'}]
commit_message:
Fix rpm build.

It appears that pyenv is incompatible with rpmbuild since setup.py
is installing files to BUILDROOT/.pyenv/... instead of using paths
that match the system python.  This file should force pyenv to use
the system python for the build.

Change-Id: I1d7deca736cfa1bb0c8ea842113ba4daa33c41fd

commit_message:
Pip install fails because of --use-mirrors parameter

Having --use-mirrors parameter in pip commands causes pip to hang on
some distros.

Pypi uses CDN for long time already, so there's no point to keep this
parameter no more.

Wipe PIP_USE_MIRRORS out of the "function" file.

Change-Id: I70adaf6591834af2482e09eb7f8f9f60df8e7692
Closes-Bug: #1069309

commit_message:
Generate heat images for tempest tests

This requires HEAT_CREATE_TEST_IMAGE to be set for any images
to be created.

If the file (files/fedora-vm-heat-cfntools-tempest.qcow2) already
exists then disk-image-create will not be called, and the existing
image file will be registered with glance. This is most likely to
happen in the following scenarios:
- a second run of stack.sh
- the image has been pre-built elsewhere (such as during devstack-gate
  image building)
Change-Id: I276573a20927e72f2cb68784f655c1ba1913ae8a

Add Cinder V2 API to keystone catalog

Support both SQL and templated keystone backend. This will add an
additional endpoint to go with v1.

commit_message:
Add NIC offload disable feature

On some ubuntu kernels with some versions
of Openvswitch and Nicira, when NIC offloading
is enabled on the adapter, the kernel may OOPS
within the openvswitch module.  There is now a flag
to attempt to disable all offload settings for the
adapter prior to openvswitch service startup.

Change-Id: I61b195c69fbb827876de1c3537cece01f36c6db0

commit_message:
Secure root password on restore from backup after root-enable

On the restore of an instance that has root enabled on it, we need
to ensure that we are correctly securing the root password so that
the password is not empty.

Fixes bug: 1211557

Change-Id: I6386b9e0573a39a6667504666556b918927abf76

commit_message:
Moves compute.rpcapi.prep_resize call to conductor

This patch moves the prep_resize logic out of scheduler.manager
and creates it on conductor.manager.ComputeTaskManager.

Partially implements bp cold-migrations-to-conductor

Change-Id: I8458071fb13505f55f8d2155c9ec5ee938b1005f

The name of the instance on success was always "unknown instance",
because the name attribute wasn't getting populated in the context,
and the text of the success message was wrong.  Success of this
action is successfully STARTING to resize.  There's still a
confirmation step.

Fixes Bug: 1210692

Change-Id: Ie8361fa222940e1ff02b581a3058a49ac16639d2
'}]
commit_message:
Fix minor bugs in the "Resize Instance" workflow

The name of the instance on success was always "unknown instance",
because the name attribute wasn't getting populated in the context,
and the text of the success message was wrong.  Success of this
action is successfully STARTING to resize.  There's still a
confirmation step.

Fixes Bug: 1210692

Change-Id: Ie8361fa222940e1ff02b581a3058a49ac16639d2

commit_message:
Fixes some puppet lint warnings

This commit fixes the following warnings:
manifests/compute/libvirt.pp - WARNING: double quoted string containing no variables on line 31
manifests/init.pp - WARNING: class inheriting from params class on line 77
manifests/migration/libvirt.pp - WARNING: case statement without a default case on line 4

Change-Id: I84a1f5edfd63973fcfa963f9acfa954cf06c094b

commit_message:
Add JobOrigin database object

Define the JobOrigin object and add database methods for
creation, lookup, and delete.  Extend the JobOrigin REST
api functions to use the database methods and manipulate
real objects.

This change adds db/models_edp.py and db/storage_edp.py to
hold database objects and methods related to EDP.

Change-Id: I7f24f3bf1e3758d4958cc3261cd0ce29536aac66
Implements: blueprint edp-job-origin-component

commit_message:
Fix signature of _create_volume() in ThinLVMVolumeDriver

create_volume_from_snapshot will call _create_volume() with the
wrong parameters when using ThinLVMVolumeDriver.  It should be
compatible with LVMVolumeDriver's _create_volume() method.

Fixes bug: 1210853

Change-Id: I18f7baf60601b3bcf01425b505a0579a826f072e

commit_message:
Removed monkeypatching of __del__ in tests

On PyPy adding __del__ to a class after it's constructed does not
work, instead implement the leakchecker in tests by using weakrefs,
which works everywhere.

Change-Id: I873efb3e2f85f731d5836bf9bf06a21e939e8542

commit_message:
Adding support to mgmt-cli for admin to create backups

Extending the management client to allow for an admin API to create
instance backups.

Addresses blueprint: admin-create-restore-backups

commit_message:
python3: Fix import compatibility

Python3 reorganized the standard library and moved several functions
to different modules. Six provides a consistent interface
to them through the fake six.moves module.

However, the urlparse, urllib2, etc modules have been combined
into one module which Six does not support so do it the old
fashioned way.

This is covered upstream but not included in six by
https://bitbucket.org/gutworth/six/pull-request/5/create-sixmovesurllib

Change-Id: I3b771c48d6663e24aa2ed6740c3cbf7dfa88065a
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

I think the code looks good, but have a possibly stupid question.
I am going to ask it - if it's really stupid please shame me publicly.

Would it work if everytime floating IPs are updated (added, removed, or reassociated), we just blank current configuration and write configuration for new ones?
This would imply removing all DNAT configurations, and writing new DNAT entries only for the new floating IPs. this should take care of the remapped ones too.

And if we apply iptables changes only once, using defer_apply, there's a chance this might actually work."}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2013-08-12 17:10:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (4 inline comments)

Salvatore, I'm assuming that your comment to remove all mappings and re-add them is referring only to the iptables half of this operation, no?  Remember that there is also the other half of the operation where the IP addresses are added/removed from the device.  Removing all IP addresses will cause some disruption in the network flow.

Given my assumption is correct, I do like your idea.  It has a stronger idempotent quality that is very desirable.

I'll work on an improved patch set today and will submit it when it is ready."}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2013-08-12 17:18:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-08-12 17:18:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Delete old floating ips before new ones are added.

It is important to delete the ips before adding new ones in the case
where an ip is reused with a new floating ip id.

This commit reorganizes this method a bit.  It uses set operations and
adds a bit of symmetry in the hopes that it will be easily reviewed.

Change-Id: I5eb97250fc60031e324ba01dce850f30340ce09d
Fixes: Bug #1209011

commit_message:
Moves extension files to routes

This allows extensions to be loaded properly without interfering with
directories in trove/extensions that are loaded as python modules.

Change-Id: Iad1bdc9b7548c46b0e5b8694693b4456ac548f14
Implements: Blueprint fix-extensions-imports

commit_message:
Revert "Conductor objects are re-populated on update"

We discarded that idea - seems to be too fragile and unreliable

commit_message:
Remove references to enable_metadata_access_network_option

Bug 1211850

This configuration variable is vestigial and not used anywhere
in the code. References to it should be removed to avoid confusion.

Change-Id: I13f86fe8b964c163324160b4c983e773e6b93e40

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-06 06:20:13.000000000', 'message': "Remove clear_rabbit_queues script

The clear_rabbit_queues script has been around forever, but it doesn't
appear to be widely used - e.g. there is no user documentation for it
and I don't see any mentions of it on mailing lists or Q&A forums.

Also, RabbitMQ now includes a management plugin and CLI which allows
you do do e.g.

  $> rabbitmqadmin delete queue name=$topic
  $> rabbitmqadmin delete queue name=$topic.$host
  $> rabbitmqadmin delete exchange name=nova

oslo.messaging does not expose an API equivalent of this command since
even the existance of a queue is transport driver specific. We could
consider adding transport-specific admin CLIs, but probably not where
the transport already has suitable admin CLIs elsewhere.

For reference, this script was added by this merge:

  https://code.launchpad.net/~mdragon/nova/lp794635/+merge/71437

blueprint: oslo.messaging
Change-Id: If5e6354e8ace4c0b4425c96de558a5cbab4c98bd
