commit_message:
Remove clear_rabbit_queues script

The clear_rabbit_queues script has been around forever, but it doesn't
appear to be widely used - e.g. there is no user documentation for it
and I don't see any mentions of it on mailing lists or Q&A forums.

Also, RabbitMQ now includes a management plugin and CLI which allows
you do do e.g.

  $> rabbitmqadmin delete queue name=$topic
  $> rabbitmqadmin delete queue name=$topic.$host
  $> rabbitmqadmin delete exchange name=nova

oslo.messaging does not expose an API equivalent of this command since
even the existance of a queue is transport driver specific. We could
consider adding transport-specific admin CLIs, but probably not where
the transport already has suitable admin CLIs elsewhere.

For reference, this script was added by this merge:

  https://code.launchpad.net/~mdragon/nova/lp794635/+merge/71437

blueprint: oslo.messaging
Change-Id: If5e6354e8ace4c0b4425c96de558a5cbab4c98bd

commit_message:
Rename client.py to httpclient.py

The discoverable entry point is to be client.Client however adding this
functionality to the current client.py is impossible as we end up with
circular dependencies.

This patch simply renames the current client.py to httpclient.py to make
future patches that will modify client.py more readable.

Required for: blueprint api-version-discovery

Change-Id: Ibcea03f6e1df0ae05329297166a8b8117fc3ce7b

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-07-22 21:11:43.000000000', 'message': "Add common methods required to allow translation of REST API responses

REST API responses (particularly errors) are always returned to
consumers in the locale of the operating system. This change adds common
methods that will be required by other components in the process of
translating the API responses to a locale requested by the API consumer.

The patch set includes the following changes:

1) An installer for the lazy _() function is provided. Services that
want to use the Message class to do delayed translation will just have
to set the new 'lazy' flag in the existing gettext.install().

2) A method to retrieve all available languages in a given translation
domain in order to pick one that will be used to translate the
response to the user.

3) A utility method to translate a Message.

Co-authored-by: Mathew Oden <mrodden@us.ibm.com>
Co-authored-by: Ben Nemec <openstack@nemebean.com>

This partially implements bp user-locale-api.

Change-Id: I27640a3c8b255be51bc6396d238098bd25af61ec

commit_message:
Add common methods required to allow translation of REST API responses

REST API responses (particularly errors) are always returned to
consumers in the locale of the operating system. This change adds common
methods that will be required by other components in the process of
translating the API responses to a locale requested by the API consumer.

The patch set includes the following changes:

1) An installer for the lazy _() function is provided. Services that
want to use the Message class to do delayed translation will just have
to set the new 'lazy' flag in the existing gettext.install().

2) A method to retrieve all available languages in a given translation
domain in order to pick one that will be used to translate the
response to the user.

3) A utility method to translate a Message.

Co-authored-by: Mathew Odden <mrodden@us.ibm.com>
Co-authored-by: Ben Nemec <openstack@nemebean.com>

This partially implements bp user-locale-api.

Change-Id: I27640a3c8b255be51bc6396d238098bd25af61ec

Previously, if you deleted a port and then created another with the same mac you would get a different ip address assigned to you since the previous one was already handed out. Port security would block you from sending out on the old lease as it would be mapped to a different ip.

I think we need something to recycle, after upgrading, all the IPs which were being held - this means allocations without a port_id.
This could be done in the migration, but then updating the allocation range would probably be impossible.

Also, the problem noted by Yong on port_update - which actually always existed - might now manifest with duplicated IPs.
the scenario would be:
1) IP for VMXXX updated via API from ip_1 to ip_2
2) dhcp_release makes ip_1 available to other VMs
3) VMYYY take ip_1 before lease on VMXXX expires
     VMYYY and VMXXX will have the same IP for a while

Before, the hold_ip mechanism kind of ensured the IP won't be reused until expired.
either we accept this or:
1) keep the hold mechanism for port updates (it's fine to use dhcp_release on delete)
2) deferring dhcp_release using either timers or dhcp-script for dnsmasq (this will cause VMYYY to not receive IPs until VMXXX expires)
3) compel the instance to release its address (is that even feasible?)"}, {'account_id': 4395, 'date': '2013-07-31 18:47:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Salvatore - Today, if you update a port to change the IP address the the instance will not be able to send out on the previous ip address that it has as the arp spoofing rules are updated to reflect this change. This to true today if using the OVS plugin. I think this is the correct behavior we want. The only area where it might get funky is if a tenant removes port_security_enabled. In that case sure this could happen but it seems obvious why and should be expected if they do that.'}, {'account_id': 4395, 'date': '2013-07-31 18:50:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: (4 inline comments)

Your point on anti spoof makes sense.
Do you think it's worth thinking about addresses which might be held when one upgrades openstack?
There's a chance the will be then held forever, isn't it?"}, {'account_id': 4395, 'date': '2013-08-01 22:34:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

In order to avoid this problem one would need to upgrade in the following order to avoid any problems:

1) Upgrade dhcp-agents; 
2) wait till dhcp-lease time has expired
3) upgrade neutron-server 

*Note: previous running dhcp-agents will still be running with the default lease time of 120seconds. There isn't anything we can do about that though unless they do pkill dnsmasq and restart the dhcp-agent as it will launch new dnsmasq process with the new lease time."}, {'account_id': 4395, 'date': '2013-08-01 23:47:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-02 00:14:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Works for me

commit_message:
Remove DHCP lease logic

Previously neutron was keeping track of dhcp lease time in order
to ensure it didn't hand out an ip address that was already leased.
This patch removes that logic and instead leverages the dhcp_release
utility. This allows us to reuse ip addresses immediately after a port
is deleted. This patch also bumps the lease time to 24 hours instead
of 2 minutes with reduces the amount of dhcp traffic.

DocImpact

There is a DocImpact for this bug related to the upgrade path. One should
first upgrade their dhcp-agents. Then wait till the dhcp_lease time has
expired. Lastly, update neutron-server in order to avoid the case where
an instance is deleted and the dnsmasq process has not released the lease
and neturon allocates that ip to a new port.

Fixes bug: 1202392
Implements blueprint: remove-dhcp-lease

Change-Id: Ifcb4f093c92904ceb896438987d53e692eb7fb26

commit_message:
Creates an empty init script override file if necessary

Without this patch, puppet runs were failing with the following error:

(/Stage[main]/Cinder::Volume::Rbd/File_line[set initscript env]) Could not
evaluate: No such file or directory - /etc/init/cinder-volume.override

Change-Id: Ibf42b4b09441c8a044f50af62246be31fe584e1b

commit_message:
Add auth config for neutron metadata proxy

 * Without auth config, the proxy will return 500 errors on
   cloud-init requests, which will cause VM connectivity
   checks to fail.
 * A cleaner fix would be for the metadata proxy to reuse the
   configuration from the keystone_authtoken section of
   neutron.conf, but I chose the easier route because of a
   pending switch from REST to RPC communication (RPC won't
   need the auth config).
 * Fixes bug 1210664

Change-Id: Iaa3c74f5ada2404119c44c8cbdad380eda158f66

commit_message:
Add some missing pkgs to Cinder install

Added python-dev even though it's picked up
by other projects already, just to be explicit.

Also added libpq-dev, this way users can just
run "sudo pip install -r test-requirements.txt"
and perform everything in run_tests.sh without the
need for venv.

Change-Id: I3953032ac40ef78fc6f67d77539e13539fbbb2ac

commit_message:
Allow disabling of debug logging

I find that enabling the debug log level often causes me to miss
important error messages due to the sheer volume of information
logged.  This change allows configuration of the debug option
in a number of the projects so it can be disabled globally
without having to make one-off changes after each re-stack.

Note that this does not apply to Keystone or Swift right now.
They use a different method to configure their logging level and
I'm not as familiar with them so I didn't want to mess with their
settings.

Change-Id: I185d496543d245a644854c8a37f3359377cb978c

Add missing quantum-plugin-cisco package resource

This is a required package to configure cisco plugin,
without this change the plugin configuration will
fail with package resource not found.

commit_message:
Clone_image method added image_id as parameter.

Clone_image method contains volume and image_location
as parameters. It needs to add additional image_id
as a parameter for driver implementations to introspect
internal image stores or registry for efficient image cloning.

blueprint clone-image-imageid

Change-Id: I20ae519492d73abecb1d0efc3b8e7204d2b2a4cb

Update impl_qpid.py to the latest from oslo-incubator.

commit_message:
Fix some NVP tests do not do cleanup of nvp ports

Some of the NVP test do not execute self.addCleanup(self.fc.reset_all)
from setUp() as NiciraPluginV2TestCase is not the first mixin.
This casuses left over ports to still exist between different testcases.
This patch only fixes this issue for TestNiciraPortsV2 and
NiciraPortSecurityTestCaseas, some of the other tests require the setUp()
for the first mixin to be called for their tests to work.

Note: this is why the tests for the Remove DHCP lease logic are failing.

Fixes bug: 1209355

Change-Id: I932471cdb8925353c5825cd70c8217511d6d7938

commit_message:
Port "Accept is_public=None .." to v3 tree

The following commit(I2a9b1c24cd744c8819c1d41e0ad103d05398401c) have
not been merged to v3 tree now, because the commit was merged to the
existing api after porting flavors.py to v3 tree.

    commit 645c2d3a06bbf8b0854ebcc539ad33dd706866c5
    Author: Xavier Queralt <xqueralt@redhat.com>
    Date:   Wed Jun 12 14:59:29 2013 +0200

        Accept is_public=None when listing all flavors

This patch ports the commit to v3 tree.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: Id1ff1366c16f0caac50e279b2add5ec9d9b9bf5f

I'm not following the need/purpose of the --metadata arg to list here?  Why not just do a volume show on the item of interest?'}, {'account_id': 6743, 'date': '2013-08-09 19:48:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Well its about finding the item.
This would allow me to list items with a specific tag or so. In my case i have over 20 results from the cinder list command. By using the --metadata I am able to filter them down to a handful for better oversight.

Basically cinder list --metadata tag=foo shows me all volumes with metadata tag=foo. Does it not sound attractive to you?'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2013-08-09 20:33:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

commit_message:
Add requirements to note that paramiko is needed

I have no idea whether projects in infra use requirements.txt,
however, I was surprised to run the script and have it fail due to
a missing module and no documentation about it being needed to be
installed :)

Your feedback welcome!

Change-Id: I0f0833a67004bfcc7649083a201086337a6d4b81

Fixes bug #1171190

Parsing block_device_mapping from strings sometimes results in
volume_size being set to '' or u''.  This causes a problem when
inserting into PostgreSQL, which insists that integer columns
actually contain integers.  Remove invalid device_size before
inserting or updating block_device_mapping database records.

(cherry picked from commit 188a94c898bcf07f9fe42ef2f3b5ee4aa8859b49)

commit_message:
Remove invalid block_device_mapping volume_size of ''

Fixes bug #1171190

Parsing block_device_mapping from strings sometimes results in
volume_size being set to '' or u''.  This causes a problem when
inserting into PostgreSQL, which insists that integer columns
actually contain integers.  Remove invalid device_size before
inserting or updating block_device_mapping database records.

(cherry picked from commit 188a94c898bcf07f9fe42ef2f3b5ee4aa8859b49)

Change-Id: I1042038f17c4eee7056261b9ececf5e4f43bfb7f

commit_message:
Bug fix pyparsing upgrade for python quantum client

The python-quantumclient package may not include the correct
version of pyparsing in its dependencies, requiring us to
ensure that it is upgraded to the latest version prior to usage.
Needed to correct tests to pass openstack-common 0.4.0 changes.

Change-Id: Ia8507a5fe94322ff3106d12d161dcedf2ee19fdd

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-12 16:53:45.000000000', 'message': "Fix handling ImageUnacceptable in create_volume

In the create_volume flow ImageUnacceptable exceptions are
not properly handled.  _copy_image_to_volume can receive an
ImageUnacceptable exception from copy_image_to_volume if fetch_to_raw
is used.  Currently the ImageUnacceptable exception is changed to
a generic ImageCopyFailure exception which does not make the cause
of the excpetion clear.

This change adds handling and raising ImageUnacceptable exceptions
in _copy_image_to_volume.  It also adds the exception to
no_reschedule_types as it doesn't make sense to keep retrying the
copy if the image was found to be unacceptable.

fixes bug 1209021

Change-Id: I9aacf23dfaaa1a4df0a869d1c9544c376488f01b
"}]
commit_message:
Fix handling ImageUnacceptable in create_volume

In the create_volume flow ImageUnacceptable exceptions are
not properly handled.  _copy_image_to_volume can receive an
ImageUnacceptable exception from copy_image_to_volume if fetch_to_raw
is used.  Currently the ImageUnacceptable exception is changed to
a generic ImageCopyFailure exception which does not make the cause
of the excpetion clear.

This change adds handling and raising ImageUnacceptable exceptions
in _copy_image_to_volume.  It also adds the exception to
no_reschedule_types as it doesn't make sense to keep retrying the
copy if the image was found to be unacceptable.

fixes bug 1209021

Change-Id: I9aacf23dfaaa1a4df0a869d1c9544c376488f01b

commit_message:
Add a unit testing configuration fixture

The configuration options registered by oslo.messaging should not be
directly relied upon by users of the library, since those config option
names could change in future.

Add an API which allows API users to override specific configuration
options e.g.

    self.messaging_conf = self.useFixture(messaging.ConfFixture(cfg.CONF))
    self.messaging_conf.transport_driver = 'fake'

Change-Id: If0d837e1b86e3b04237fde522551cfb81505a543

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-12 21:49:28.000000000', 'message': "Add a TransportURL class to the public API

Nova's cells/rpc_driver.py has some code which allows user of the REST
API to update elements of a cell's transport URL (say, the host name of
the message broker) stored in the database. To achieve this, it has
a parse_transport_url() method which breaks the URL into its constituent
parts and an unparse_transport_url() which re-forms it again after
updating some of its parts.

This is all fine and, since it's fairly specialized, it wouldn't be a
big deal to leave this code in Nova for now ... except the unparse
method looks at CONF.rpc_backend to know what scheme to use in the
returned URL if now backend was specified.

oslo.messaging registers the rpc_backend option, but the ability to
reference any option registered by the library should not be relied upon
by users of the library. Imagine, for instance, if we renamed the option
in future (with backwards compat for old configurations), then this
would mean API breakage.

So, long story short - an API along these lines makes some sense, but
especially since not having it would mean we'd need to add some way to
query the name of the transport driver.

In this commit, we add a simple new TransportURL class:

  >>> url = messaging.TransportURL.parse(cfg.CONF, 'foo:///')
  >>> str(url), url
  ('foo:///', <TransportURL transport='foo'>)
  >>> url.hosts.append(messaging.TransportHost(hostname='localhost'))
  >>> str(url), url
  ('foo://localhost/', <TransportURL transport='foo', hosts=[<TransportHost hostname='localhost'>]>)
  >>> url.transport = None
  >>> str(url), url
  ('kombu://localhost/', <TransportURL transport='kombu', hosts=[<TransportHost hostname='localhost'>]>)
  >>> cfg.CONF.set_override('rpc_backend', 'bar')
  >>> str(url), url
  ('bar://localhost/', <TransportURL transport='bar', hosts=[<TransportHost hostname='localhost'>]>)

The TransportURL.parse() method equates to parse_transport_url() and
TransportURL.__str__() equates to unparse_transport().

The transport drivers are also updated to take a TransportURL as a
required argument, which simplifies the handling of transport URLs in
the drivers.

Change-Id: Ic04173476329858e4a2c2d2707e9d4aeb212d127

commit_message:
Add a TransportURL class to the public API

Nova's cells/rpc_driver.py has some code which allows user of the REST
API to update elements of a cell's transport URL (say, the host name of
the message broker) stored in the database. To achieve this, it has
a parse_transport_url() method which breaks the URL into its constituent
parts and an unparse_transport_url() which re-forms it again after
updating some of its parts.

This is all fine and, since it's fairly specialized, it wouldn't be a
big deal to leave this code in Nova for now ... except the unparse
method looks at CONF.rpc_backend to know what scheme to use in the
returned URL if now backend was specified.

oslo.messaging registers the rpc_backend option, but the ability to
reference any option registered by the library should not be relied upon
by users of the library. Imagine, for instance, if we renamed the option
in future (with backwards compat for old configurations), then this
would mean API breakage.

So, long story short - an API along these lines makes some sense, but
especially since not having it would mean we'd need to add some way to
query the name of the transport driver.

In this commit, we add a simple new TransportURL class:

  >>> url = messaging.TransportURL.parse(cfg.CONF, 'foo:///')
  >>> str(url), url
  ('foo:///', <TransportURL transport='foo'>)
  >>> url.hosts.append(messaging.TransportHost(hostname='localhost'))
  >>> str(url), url
  ('foo://localhost/', <TransportURL transport='foo', hosts=[<TransportHost hostname='localhost'>]>)
  >>> url.transport = None
  >>> str(url), url
  ('kombu://localhost/', <TransportURL transport='kombu', hosts=[<TransportHost hostname='localhost'>]>)
  >>> cfg.CONF.set_override('rpc_backend', 'bar')
  >>> str(url), url
  ('bar://localhost/', <TransportURL transport='bar', hosts=[<TransportHost hostname='localhost'>]>)

The TransportURL.parse() method equates to parse_transport_url() and
TransportURL.__str__() equates to unparse_transport().

The transport drivers are also updated to take a TransportURL as a
required argument, which simplifies the handling of transport URLs in
the drivers.

Change-Id: Ic04173476329858e4a2c2d2707e9d4aeb212d127

commit_message:
Port os-volumes extension to v3 API Part 1

This patch only copies the v2 files (implementation and test)
into the appropriate v3 directories unchanged. The copy as-is
will not be loaded by either the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The
second changeset will then make the changes required for it to
work as a v3 extension.

This is being done in order to make reviewing of extension porting
easier as gerrit will display only what is actually changed for v3
rather than entirely new files

Partially implements blueprint: improve-block-device-handling
Partially implements blueprint: nova-v3-api

Change-Id: Icf77ad0090647a9c9cdfc5af2f6c12cad5d6f6e8

Probably should be fixed in a separate patch though."}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-07-31 22:55:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Do not merge

Due to https://review.openstack.org/#/c/38228/ this file is about to be moved into a new repo. Could you please re-submit this change once the new repository has been set up?

Having said that, we *strongly* recommend that users use python-heatclient instead of heat-cfn for their daily heat usage (and would be interested to hear any reasons why you cannot do that).'}, {'account_id': 7148, 'date': '2013-08-01 14:33:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

Zane, thanks for your comments. Taking a look at the estimate_template_cost implementation, it's true that <stackname> is not required. And I am also little curious why it only return a url http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratis for the implementations...

Steve, thanks for your information. I will abandon this patch and resubmit it after that get merged. I am a new heat user. Just trying to get familiar with heat cfn functions asap and used to use CLI as a habit.:)  REST calls will be used for official management work and API exploiter work when I become more familiar."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-08-01 19:19:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
heat-cfn help estimate-template-cost throw out 'NoneType' exception

"heat-cfn help estimate-template-cost" does not return correct help message
but throw out 'NoneType' error. Add help doc in the estimate_template_cost
method to fix it.

Fixes: bug 1205601
Change-Id: I9489fba1885d958be9b0a9f698eba0a402532487

commit_message:
Allow passing a logging level to processutils.execute

Previously, processutils.execute always logged what commands were
run at DEBUG level.  This is usually fine, but sometimes the caller
wants to log particularly important commands at INFO level instead,
and oslo should allow that.

Change-Id: I89af6fdc0bb11a4134aaaca417a54ba3b515ca7e

@nikola, I put some thought on your comment, I, unfortunately,  think there's no better way to do this. We could re-use the mnt variable somehow but that would just overload that parameter and make it incompatible with older versions.

Checking Qemu's version wouldn't work either since that would be just assuming it was built with Gluster's support, which can be disabled at compile time.

If folks have better ideas, I'll be very happy to revisit / apply them.

commit_message:
Add option for QEMU Gluster libgfapi support

If gluster is present in qemu_allowed_storage_drivers, glusterfs's
backend will pass a disk configuration to QEMU. This allows QEMU to
access the volume using libgfapi rather than mounting GlusterFS via
fuse.

Implements blueprint glusterfs-native-support
DocImpact

Co-authored-by: Flavio Percoco <flavio@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I939cac05ee333b77abcaa9bd132d5eb3308e60ff

commit_message:
Move heat-cfn, heat-boto, heat-watch to new repo

The new home for these tools is
https://github.com/openstack-dev/heat-cfnclient

These tools are now aimed at heat developers only
and they will not be released or packaged.

Change-Id: I1ea62ef17e81ab53cacb5e4940f0c4e2516ed383

The Oslo notifier api lost add_driver(), and nova copy of that code has
been updated recently, so that broke Ceilometer testing of that piece.
Fix it by using another mechanism to test.

Change-Id: I0169fcc9955501d490dfcdd7742205ea5c9ba15b
Closes-Bug: #1211532
'}]
commit_message:
Fix nova test_notifier wrt new notifier API

The Oslo notifier api lost add_driver(), and nova copy of that code has
been updated recently, so that broke Ceilometer testing of that piece.
Fix it by using another mechanism to test.

Change-Id: I0169fcc9955501d490dfcdd7742205ea5c9ba15b
Closes-Bug: #1211532

commit_message:
Fix intermittent failure in autoscaling tests

Tests for autoscaling suspend and resume sometimes fail because of an
order issue. The branch changes the mock calls to not rely on order.

Change-Id: I74bcde5c6b486fecbb2c2ed0685ce18c786aa974

commit_message:
Sync models with migrations

Fixed bugs:
- wrong type instead of MediumText (InstanceInfoCache, Instance, ComputeNode),
- skipped indexes (SecurityGroup, Instance),
- wrong length of column (ComputeNodeStat),
- wrong order of columns in index (KeyPair),
- missing name of UniwueConstraint (InstanceGroup).

bp: db-sync-models-with-migrations

Change-Id: Id698fabd553a10326d984f88fc9580d88cd2a22e

I was puzzled by that getVersion is not accessible from a read-only connection. Perhaps my understanding wrong of the below from http://www.libvirt.org/html/libvirt-libvirt.html
or I am looking at the wrong thing. "may" is a weak word.
Definitely if this is true, I should be checking for a return value of -1 as opposed to an exception being thrown.

Will fix the commit message. There were a bunch of other failures in the full test which makes me wonder if other calling routines might not have access to authentication credentials. Yet to investigate.

Regards
Malini



virConnectGetVersion
int	virConnectGetVersion		(virConnectPtr conn,
					 unsigned long * hvVer)
Get the version level of the Hypervisor running. This may work only with hypervisor call, i.e. with privileged access to the hypervisor, not with a Read-Only connection.

conn
pointer to the hypervisor connection
hvVer
return value for the version of the running hypervisor (OUT)
Returns
-1 in case of error, 0 otherwise. if the version can't be extracted by lack of capacities returns 0 and @hvVer is 0, otherwise @hvVer value is major * 1,000,000 + minor * 1,000 + release

commit_message:
Enforce authenticated connections to libvirt

Authenticated connections for both reads and writes
increases VM security.

The virConnectOpenAuth API is flexible, it effectively
obsoletes virConnectOpen and virConnectOpenReadOnly.
ReadOnly access, with its reduced access to the API,
is obtained by passing in the vir connect flag
VIR_CONNECT_RO (=1)

An added advantage of using openAuth is the fewer API calls
that need to be maintained in the nova libvirt driver.

Removed virConnectOpenReadOnly methods and tests.

Change-Id: I6cb3825d1225807955177d7500899babbb569e20

commit_message:
Convert "outgoing" literals to unicode

The patch convers most literals throughout marconi to unicode. Lietrals
not leaving "marconi-land" were left untouched.

This is the first patch of a serie that will enforce unicode usage
within marconi. Decode early, encode late.

String format parameters were left untouched on purpose. Those
parameters should be decoded before getting there.

Implements blueprint enforce-decoding

Change-Id: I85e534ced188191c9c7a17e9908cb720e7d63ca9

commit_message:
Fix leaking of image BDMs

Patch Ia89d531be71c460f1f82fcfce34b270639a23061 introduce creating an
image block device for every instance, to comply with the new block
device format being introduced currently.

However, due to a mistake during rebase the needed code to delete those
once the instance was being deleted was broken (even though comments
suggest otherwise).

This patch now fixes this issue, by adding a proper flag to the
conductor call when getting BDMs in compute manager's _complete_deletion
method.

Fixes bug: #1206890

Change-Id: I6a9673758b0762f99f27860b8f88a16127da7399

commit_message:
Remove unneccessary Property constraints from unit tests

It doesn't really make a lot of sense to have constraints on the number of
keys in a Map Property, or on the allowed values in a List Property. In
both cases, we can and should define the Schema for each item. Neither is
used anywhere in the code, since the new Schema/Constraints do not allow
it, and SchemaTest.test_all_resource_schemata() tests that all existing
schemata are valid.

Change-Id: I24e11ec59c75ef770bf040ee8151bbe061f4a864

commit_message:
xenapi: Use a jeos vm as a template

DevStack was using templating to speed up the setup process with
XenServer. The template already included some devstack customisations,
not just a clean OS. This change modifies devstack behaviour, so that
the template is a simple clean operating system. This makes it easier to
use custom OS as a template, potentially speeding up the tests.

related to blueprint xenapi-devstack-cleanup

commit_message:
fix permission issues around dist-packages

As we are installing pip packages with root, the permissions sometimes
go wrong, thus we can't access the files with a regular user. This patch
adds a fix - recursively adding read permissions on the relevan
directories.

Fixes bug 1210520

Change-Id: Ic61d0dca64d9d20335339bde5bf79714052246de

subject: Add domains support to cli api
messages:
[{'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-07-10 17:25:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

Thanks, it was my ignorance of what was required here that has left this undone...

Do we think we need the _ID versions of the domain options? I've never used --os-tenant-id for example.

Also, it would be nice to have a quick outline of what combinations of options are required, ie you only need --os-user-domain-name OR --os-project-domain-name, or whatever to do a non-default domain auth."}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-07-10 18:04:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

domain id's are a bit special in only one regard-- in a single domain deployment (probably the common use case), the domain ID is well known to be 'default' (keystone creates this out of the box via db_sync, for example), and it's a bit of a hassle to change that to something else (whereas the domain name is easily modifiable by the end user). clients can therefore safely assume that any domain ID is 'default' unless the end user specifies something else (either a domain name or another ID)"}, {'account_id': 4703, 'date': '2013-07-10 19:31:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The aim of this patch is to reflect keystone REST api to openstackclient CLI api. As keystone already has all required business logic which handles all variations of parameters I tried to make patch as simple as possible with no additional business logic. Just passing them as they are.

Due to lack of keystone documentation I used source code to make it work. Here are some test cases I used and what I understand

prerequisites:
1) openstack --os-token openstack --os-url http://172.18.194.178:35357/v3 --os-identity-api-version 3 domain create mydomain
2) openstack --os-token openstack --os-url http://172.18.194.178:35357/v3 --os-identity-api-version 3 project create myproject --domain mydomain
3) openstack --os-token openstack --os-url http://172.18.194.178:35357/v3 --os-identity-api-version 3 user create myuser --password test --domain mydomain
4) openstack --os-token openstack --os-url http://172.18.194.178:35357/v3 --os-identity-api-version 3 role add admin --user myuser --project myproject
5) openstack --os-token openstack --os-url http://172.18.194.178:35357/v3 --os-identity-api-version 3 role add admin --user myuser --domain mydomain

1. Authenticate with user from non-default domain
- setup v3 endpoints in the keystone

openstack --os-identity-api-version 3 --os-auth-url http://172.18.194.178:5000/v3 --os-username myuser --os-password test --os-user-domain-name mydomain --os-domain-name mydomain user list

works with -id as well

2. Authenticate with user in v2.0
- setup v2.0 endpoints in the keystone

openstack --os-identity-api-version 2.0 --os-auth-url http://172.18.194.178:5000/v2.0 --os-username admin --os-tenant-name admin --os-password openstack user list


Let me explain a bit more duplication of domains in the first test case.
--os-user-domain is a domain which is used for searching the user here https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/stable/grizzly/keystone/identity/backends/sql.py#L664
whereas --os-domain is a scoped domain. If you don't pass it - keystone won't return endpoints https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/stable/grizzly/keystone/auth/token_factory.py#L177

To understand more scoped/regular domains - see _do_auth here https://github.com/openstack/python-keystoneclient/blob/master/keystoneclient/v3/client.py#L159 (openstackclient uses keystoneclient)"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-07-18 06:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-07-18 06:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Some random thought

How about [^a-zA-Z0-9] ?

- Is regexp allowed for int attribute?
(IMO, we should check attribute type)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-25 08:38:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

nati:
Q: How about check the filter values is regexp or not?
not easy to do it. because
neutron net-list --name ne --name_x_query_regex wil return net1 network. It is not clear if the 'ne' is a regexp if we have no obvious indicator, which is --name_x_query_regex."}, {'account_id': 2874, 'date': '2013-07-25 10:25:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-25 10:47:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- http://logs.openstack.org/00/38600/2/check/gate-neutron-pep8/930 : SUCCESS in 1m 59s
- http://docs-draft.openstack.org/00/38600/2/check/gate-neutron-docs/930/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 57s
- http://logs.openstack.org/00/38600/2/check/gate-neutron-python26/928 : SUCCESS in 22m 29s
- http://logs.openstack.org/00/38600/2/check/gate-neutron-python27/929 : SUCCESS in 15m 44s
- http://logs.openstack.org/00/38600/2/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-neutron/7412 : SUCCESS in 18m 52s (non-voting)
'}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2013-07-25 14:20:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Do not merge

(1 inline comment)

This feature has changed substantially from the original issue and as implemented does not fully agree with the linked blueprint.  The original the idea was to make Tempest compatible searching for IP addresses via the % operator.

I don't think this is the proper direction to take at the current time without a bigger discussion on cross database support, CLI interaction, and how it works for any plugin that does not want to use the database (it is technically still an option).  To me this feels like something to discuss in Hong Kong vs something we merge in H3."}, {'account_id': 2874, 'date': '2013-07-25 16:18:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

mark mcclain,
I don't think this patch has gone astray. the behavior is compatible with nova's way. We have added the {attr}_x_query_regex because our API is using in_ by default.

All the change is compatible with current API."}, {'account_id': 2874, 'date': '2013-07-25 16:18:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Salvatore Orlando,
What is your opinion?

Regards,
Yong Sheng Gong'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-07-26 06:10:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I might be simplistic and ignoring some fundamental things, but in general a regex-based evaluation and a like operation are not the same.

I mean, a like operation is a regex-based evaluation, but the opposite is not true. It would be good if we could satisfy the tempest requirement for having LIKE filters in list operations without having to introduce DB-backend awareness in the db base plugin class. I haven't explored its feasibility, though.

For plugins which do not wish to use the database, regex-based evaluations are probably just one of the issues they will have to face given that now we're excessively reliant on the db base plugin class.

Regarding the 'nova does this' comments, my personal, non-constraining, opinion is that this does not constitute a motivation strong enough for doing the same thing in Neutron."}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-07-26 07:35:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I've chatted with Yong over IRC.

The bottom line is that we need regex-based filters if
- we want to fill the gap with the nova's IP filtering capability (and this assume we say it's ok to have regex based filters in Neutron)
- we agree that it is worth fixing the tempest issue in Havana release and that regex expressions are the only way for fixing it"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-03 06:03:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
allow regex in List operation of API

&{attr}_x_query_regex=xx is used to indicate the attr query
is using regex. We don't allow regex query on attrs of number
or bool type.

for neutron client:
neutron net-create net1
'neutron net-list --name ne --name_x_query_regex' without change of
current client.
'neutron net-list --name action=regex ne' with updated neutron client.

Change-Id: I705b045132f4627f4c5c5666a34f5f405f21fb68
Implements: blueprint like-op-list
Fixes: Bug #1182883

commit_message:
change requirements to point to PyPam not pam.

This changes the python requirements file to point to PyPam which
is used in the scripts rather than pam which has been taken out.
It it necessary to fix dependencies in some linux distros such
as Mageia.

Change-Id: Id45e17f8224e39519a9ca7d9a0a665e04165d92c

commit_message:
Extend, structure Keystone troubleshooting section

This patch creates a new section in common for identity
troubleshooting, which supercedes the existing stub sections
in common and openstack install and adds PKI middleware
troubleshooting information.

The section is included in the basic install guide
(install identity chapter) and compute admin manual
(via the common identity chapter that is only used in this guide).

fixes bug 1204640

Conflicts:
	doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_identity_mgmt.xml
	doc/src/docbkx/common/section_identity_troubleshooting.xml
	doc/src/docbkx/openstack-install/identity-troubleshooting.xml

Change-Id: Ibce5d404d1a5d1c413f1324c897eca4b36f6edf2
bp:restructure-documentation

will make challenge to volume features such as resize, backup. Cinder now makes
a great progress on volume management and Trove can follow it via using Cinder
API.

Trove needs to remove the path to create volume via Nova which is implemented
by virt backend like libvirt.

implement bp unified-creating-volume-path

Change-Id: I7402dd871f5b6e615aba888026685254f60a2e2d
'}]
commit_message:
Unified creating volume path via Cinder

Now Trove supports two creating volume path corresponds to Nova and CInder. It
will make challenge to volume features such as resize, backup. Cinder now makes
a great progress on volume management and Trove can follow it via using Cinder
API.

Trove needs to remove the path to create volume via Nova which is implemented
by virt backend like libvirt.

implement bp unified-creating-volume-path

Change-Id: I7402dd871f5b6e615aba888026685254f60a2e2d

[{'created': '2013-08-10 11:59:37.000000000', 'message': 'Reword H404 description to match check

The check only checks that a multiline docstring starts
without a newline. The message "should start with a summary"
is misleading reviewers, as can be seen in e.g.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/40114/

The "check for summary at beginning being less than 80 chars
and end with punctation" needs to be moved to a new hacking check
to preserve compatibility.

Change-Id: I694b0dc55706ccf8ada9bb132cc7efb3c49cd0d6
'}]
commit_message:
Reword H404 description to match check

The check only checks that a multiline docstring starts
without a newline. The message "should start with a summary"
is misleading reviewers, as can be seen in e.g.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/40114/

The "check for summary at beginning being less than 80 chars
and end with punctation" needs to be moved to a new hacking check
to preserve compatibility.

Change-Id: I694b0dc55706ccf8ada9bb132cc7efb3c49cd0d6
